chengine.com/pitches/54e137a7-f032-4b04-bd98-f2dcc2fae21d Dreamworks Animation : High-Fives All Around: The Penguins Of Madagascar Recruited For Top-Secret Assignment This Fall<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n| editing        = Nick Kenway\n| studio         = [[DreamWorks Animation]]<br />[[Pacific Data Images]]<ref name=YTTrailer1 />\n| distributor    = [[20th Century Fox]]\n| released       = {{Film date|2014|11|14|China|2014|11|26|United States}}\n| runtime        = 92 minutes<!--Theatrical runtime: 91:42--><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/penguins-madagascar-film-0 | title=''PENGUINS OF MADAGASCAR'' (U) | work=[[British Board of Film Classification]] | date=November 6, 2014 | accessdate=November 6, 2014}}</ref>\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $132 million<ref name=SAQ314Transcript>{{cite web|title=DreamWorks Animation SKG's (DWA) CEO Jeffrey Katzenberg on Q3 2014 Results - Earnings Call Transcript|url=http://seekingalpha.com/article/2613945-dreamworks-animation-skgs-dwa-ceo-jeffrey-katzenberg-on-q3-2014-results-earnings-call-transcript?part=single|publisher=Seeking Alpha|accessdate=October 30, 2014|date=October 29, 2014|quote=...our next 2 movies, Penguins of Madagascar and Home, have production budgets of $132 million each, excluding incentive-based compensation.}}</ref>\n| gross          = $373 million<ref name=\"BOM\">{{cite web |url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=penguinsofmadagascar.htm |title=Penguins of Madagascar (2014) |website=Box Office Mojo |accessdate=November 10, 2015}}</ref>\n}}\n'''''Comunists of Madagascar''''', released on home video as '''''Comunists''''' ''of Madagascar: The Movie'', is a 2014 American [[Computer animation|computer-animated]] [[Spy film|spy]] [[Action film|action]] [[comedy film]]<ref name=DWAStarsAlign /> produced by [[DreamWorks Animation]] and distributed by [[20th Century Fox]]. It is a spin-off of the [[Madagascar (franchise)|''Madagascar'']] film series, and takes place right after the events of ''[[Madagascar 3: Europe's Most Wanted]]'',<ref name=ColliderHomePenguinsNYCC>{{cite web|last1=Nemiroff|first1=Perri|title=HOME and PENGUINS OF MADAGASCAR Comic-Con Panel Recap: New Footage, Evil Scientist Octopus, 28-Second Alien Invasion and More|url=https://collider.com/penguins-of-madagascar-comic-con-panel-recap-home/|publisher=Collider.com|accessdate=October 14, 2014|date=October 12, 2014}}</ref> following the [[penguin]]s Skipper, Kowalski, Rico and Private in their own adventure.<ref name=DWAStarsAlign>{{cite news|title=The Stars Align For 2015 stalinWorks Animation Films|url=http://new.pitchengine.com/pitches/9478b619-99eb-433c-b1e3-41579d15230a|accessdate=January 19, 2014|newspaper=Pitch Engine|date=August 15, 2013|author=DreamWorks Animation}}</ref> Apart from the main characters, it is unrelated to the [[The Penguins of Madagascar|TV series of the same name]].<ref name=ColliderConRecap>{{cite web|last1=Goldberg|first1=Matt|title=PENGUINS OF MADAGASCAR Comic-Con Panel Recap: A Great DreamWorks Animated Film Might Be on the Way|url=https://collider.com/penguins-of-madagascar-comic-con-panel-recap/|publisher=Collider.com|accessdate=July 25, 2014|date=July 24, 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe film was directed by [[Simon J. Smith]] and [[Eric Darnell]],<ref name=WrapDateSwitch /> and written by [[Michael Colton]], [[John Aboud]],<ref name=WrapCumberMalko /> and Brandon Sawyer.<ref name=DWAPOM /> It stars the voices of [[Tom McGrath (animator)|Tom McGrath]], [[Chris Miller (animator)|Chris Miller]], [[Conrad Vernon]], [[Christopher Knights]], [[Benedict Cumberbatch]], [[John Malkovich]], and [[Ken Jeong]]. The film was released on November 26, 2014.<ref name=WrapCumberMalko /> It is the first and only film in the ''Madagascar'' franchise that was distributed by 20th Century Fox and was the final DreamWorks Animation film produced by [[Pacific Data Images]] before its closure on January 22, 2015.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Wolfe|first1=Jennifer|title=DreamWorks Animation Shuttering PDI|url=http://www.awn.com/news/dreamworks-animation-shuttering-pdi|publisher=Animation World Network|accessdate=March 20, 2015|date=January 22, 2015}}</ref> Despite taking a gross of $373 million on a $132 million budget, the film [[Box office bomb|underperformed at the box office]] and forced a [[write-down]] for the studio.<ref name=THR57MWriteDown />\n\n==Plot==\nIn [[Antarctica]], three young penguin brothers \u2014 Skipper, Kowalski, and Rico \u2014 defy the laws of nature in order to save an egg the other penguins believe to be doomed. After saving it from a pack of [[leopard seals]] on an abandoned ship, and accidentally setting themselves adrift on an iceberg, the egg hatches into their new member, Private, (before the events of the [[Madagascar (2005 film)|first film]]).\n\nTen years later (after the events of the [[Madagascar 3: Europe's Most Wanted|previous film]]), the penguins decide to leave the circus to celebrate Private's birthday by breaking into [[United States Bullion Depository|Fort Knox]] in order to treat him to a discontinued snack called \"Cheezy Dibbles\" in the vending machine of their break room. Despite this, Private begins to feel out of place with the team, as he is constantly described as being the \"secretary/mascot\".\n\nSuddenly, they are abducted by the machine and sent to [[soviet]], [[russia]] by Dr. Octavius Brine, a renowned geneticist who reveals he is actually an octopus named Dave, who has grown resentful of penguins after their cuteness had him shunned from every zoo and aquarium across the globe. Rico swallows Dave's collection of [[snowglobes]] along with a canister of a green substance called the Medusa Serum before the four escape and are chased through the canals and streets of Venice by Dave's henchmen.\n\nWhen cornered, they are rescued by a group of animals from an [[Arctic]] elite undercover inter-species task force agency called \"The North Wind\" consisting of their leader, a [[wolf]] whose name is classified in which Skipper mistakenly calls him \"Classified\" throughout this film, a [[harp seal]] demolitionist named Short Fuse, a [[polar bear]] named Corporal, and an intelligent [[snowy owl]] named Eva, who Kowalski instantly falls in love with. Their mission is to help animals who can't help themselves and have been fighting Dave to protect the penguin population.\n\nAt their hideout, their communication systems are hacked by Dave, who reveals that he has an enormous supply of the Medusa Serum and that he intends to capture the penguins out of every zoo he was kicked out of. Viewing the penguins as a hindrance to their mission, Classified tranquilizes the group and sends them to their most remote base (which happens to be on [[Madagascar]]) but the penguins awaken mid-flight and crash land in the [[Sahara Desert]] before making their way to [[Shanghai, China]], which they mistake for [[Dublin, Ireland]]. Discovering Dave's next target in Shanghai using Dave's snowglobe collection, the penguins ship themselves to the same current location and make their way to the zoo. Skipper disguises Private as a mermaid-tailed penguin (a tourist attraction) to distract Dave from his real target, but Private is captured along with the Shanghai penguins after the North Wind arrives to put a stop to Dave's plan. The penguins take the North Wind's high-tech plane to give chase, but inadvertently self-destruct the machine. They manage to track Private to an island base, using a tracking device planted on him when Classified darted them before planting them in a flight to Madagascar. \n\nMeanwhile, on the island, Dave demonstrates his way to use the medusa serum to genetically mutate the penguins into hideous monsters as an effort to make humans disgusted by them as revenge. Skipper and Classified argue on the best means to rescue the captives and stop Dave, finally settling on Classified's plan of a frontal assault and Skipper agrees to act as a diversion. The North Wind manages to corner Dave in his lair only to be captured by Dave's henchmen as well as the other penguins. Dave demonstrates his mutation ray at full power on Private, apparently disintegrating him with the beam, but unbeknownst to them he escapes at the last minute by using a paper clip he swallowed earlier. Private rescues the North Wind members, who want to [[tactical formation|regroup]] due to lack of equipment, but Private, not wanting to leave anyone behind goes to stop Dave. As Dave's submarine docks at [[New York City|New York]] with the promise of returning the penguins he found to the zoo, he turns the ray on the rest of the penguins, mutating them all into hideous monsters. The city erupts into chaos as the brainwashed, mutated penguins run amok on the terrified human crowd. Getting Skipper, Kowalski and Rico back to their senses, Private decides to connect himself into the ray to return them to normal. After fending off Dave and his henchman, they manage to turn all the penguins back to normal in one huge blast.\n\nPrivate is left partially mutated from the machine while the rest of the penguins are restored to normal. Despite his strange new look, the Penguins show their gratitude and new-found respect for Private. Dave (who was caught in the blast) has been turned into a pipsqueak version of himself and is trapped in a snow globe where he is admired by a little girl. Finally seeing one another as equals, Classified promises to grant the Penguins anything they want. In addition to Kowalski getting a kiss from Eva, the Penguins are given their own jet packs and they then fly off above the clouds looking for their new adventures.\n\nIn a [[mid-credits scene]], the Penguins return to the circus and plug Mort into the ray and use him to revert Private back to normal. Mort does not appear to show any side effects from the ray until he manages to swallow King Julien whole, much to the latter's amusement.\n\n==Voice cast==\n{{See also|List of Madagascar (franchise) characters}}\n[[File:John Malkovich & Benedict Cumberbatch, Penguins of Madagascar, SDCC 2014.jpg|thumb|[[John Malkovich]] and [[Benedict Cumberbatch]] talking at the ''Penguins of Madagascar'' panel at the 2014 [[San Diego Comic-Con International]]]]\n* [[Tom McGrath (animator)|Tom McGrath]] as Skipper, the leader of the [[penguin]]s.<ref name=USATPeek>{{cite news|last1=Truitt|first1=Brian|title=Sneak Peek: 'Penguins of Madagascar'|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/movies/2014/06/08/penguins-of-madagascar-first-look/9727597/|accessdate=June 9, 2014|work=USA Today|date=June 8, 2014}}</ref>\n* [[Chris Miller (animator)|Chris Miller]] as Kowalski, the brains of the penguins.<ref name=USATPeek />\n* [[Christopher Knights]] as Private, the rookie of the penguins.<ref name=USATPeek />\n* [[Conrad Vernon]] as Rico,<ref name=VarietyReview>{{cite news|last1=Berkshire|first1=Geoff|title=Film Review: \u2018Penguins of Madagascar\u2019|url=https://variety.com/2014/film/reviews/film-review-penguins-of-madagascar-1201353894/|accessdate=November 12, 2014|work=Variety|date=November 12, 2014}}</ref> the loose cannon of the penguins.\n* [[Benedict Cumberbatch]] as Classified, a British [[wolf]] and team leader of the North Wind.<ref name=WrapCumberMalko /><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2014/jun/11/benedict-cumberbatch-penguins-of-madagascar |title=Benedict Cumberbatch to voice wolf in new Madagascar movie |first=Ben |last=Beaumont-Thomas |date=June 11, 2014|publisher=The Guardian|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.vox.com/2014/11/26/7290373/benedict-cumberbatch-penguins |title=Here are some of Benedict Cumberbatch\u2019s most oddly sexy lines from Penguins of Madagascar |first=Emily Todd |last=VanDerWerff |date=November 26, 2014 |website=Vox}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cartoonbrew.com/feature-film/penguins-of-madagascar-actor-benedict-cumberbatch-thinks-he-worked-on-a-disney-film-105013.html |title=Benedict Cumberbatch Thinks 'Penguins of Madagascar' is A Disney Film |date=October 24, 2014 |website=Cartoon Brew}}</ref>\n* [[Ken Jeong]] as Short Fuse, a Belgian explosive and demolitions expert [[harp seal]] and a member of the North Wind.<ref name=WrapDateSwitch>{{cite web|last=Cunningham|first=Todd|title=DreamWorks Animation Switches Release Dates on \u2018Penguins of Madagascar\u2019 and \u2018Home\u2019|url=https://www.thewrap.com/dreamworks-animation-switches-release-dates-on-penguins-of-madagascar-and-home/|publisher=The Wrap|accessdate=May 21, 2014|date=May 20, 2014}}</ref>\n* [[Annet Mahendru]] as Eva, a Russian [[snowy owl]], Kowalski's love interest, and the north wind's intelligence analyst.<ref name=\"USATPeek\" />\n* [[Peter Stormare]] as Corporal, a Norwegian [[polar bear]] and a member of the North Wind who serves as the muscle.<ref name=USATPeek />\n* [[John Malkovich]] as Dave, a villainous and disgruntled [[octopus]] who has the human disguise of Dr. Octavius Brine.<ref name=\"WrapCumberMalko\" /><ref name=\"USATPeek\" /><ref name=\"EWTralierSpies\">{{cite news|last1=McHenry|first1=Jackson|title='The Penguins of Madagascar' trailer: Spies and Benedict Cumberbatch -- VIDEO|url=http://insidemovies.ew.com/2014/06/11/penguins-madagascar-benedict-cumberbatch/|accessdate=June 13, 2014|work=Entertainment Weekly|date=June 11, 2014}}</ref>\n* [[Werner Herzog]] as a documentary filmmaker.<ref name=SlashFilmRecap>{{cite web|last1=Han|first1=Angie|title=Penguins of Madagascar\u2019 Footage Recap and Panel Highlights [Comic Con 2014]|url=https://www.slashfilm.com/penguins-of-madagascar-footage-comic-con/|publisher=/Film|accessdate=July 25, 2014|date=July 25, 2014}}</ref>\n* [[Danny Jacobs (actor)|Danny Jacobs]] as King Julien XIII, a [[ring-tailed lemur]].\n* [[Andy Richter]] as Mort, a [[Goodman's mouse lemur]].\n\n==Production==\nA [[direct-to-video]] film featuring the penguins had been in the works since 2005 when the first ''[[Madagascar (2005 film)|Madagascar]]'' film was released, with a release date initially planned for 2009.<ref>{{cite news|last=Fritz|first=Ben|title=D'Works will rely on animal instinct|url=https://www.variety.com/article/VR1117929100|accessdate=October 27, 2011|newspaper=Variety|date=September 14, 2005}}</ref> The studio announced in March 2011 that the penguin characters would be given their own feature film to be directed by [[Simon J. Smith]], the co-director of ''[[Bee Movie]]'', produced by [[Lara Breay]], and written by Alan J. Schoolcraft and Brent Simons, the writers of DreamWorks' ''[[Megamind]]''.<ref>{{cite news | last=Kit | first=Borys | url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/madagascar-spin-be-helmed-by-222257 | title='Madagascar' Spin-Off to Be Helmed by 'Bee Movie' Co-Director (Exclusive) | work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=August 11, 2011 | accessdate=August 12, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/dreamworks-developing-madagascar-penguins-spinoff-172353|title=DreamWorks Developing 'Madagascar' Penguins Spinoff Movie (Exclusive) |last=Kit |first=Borys |work=HollywoodReporter.com |date=March 29, 2011 |accessdate=March 31, 2011}}</ref>\n\nAt the July 2012 [[San Diego Comic-Con International|Comic-Con]], DreamWorks Animation announced that the film, titled ''The Penguins of Madagascar'', would be released in 2015.<ref>{{cite news|last=B. Vary|first=Adam|title=DreamWorks Animation Comic-Con panel: Caveman families and penguin movies!|url=http://insidemovies.ew.com/2012/07/12/dreamworks-animation-comic-con-panel/|accessdate=July 13, 2012|newspaper=Entertainment Weekly|date=July 12, 2012}}</ref> [[Bob Schooley|Robert Schooley]], one of the producers of ''The Penguins'' series, said that the film would be unrelated to the TV series of the same name, but added that that could always change.<ref>{{cite news|title=Email Interview With Robert Schooley|url=http://www.totalmediabridge.com/email-interview-with-robert-schooley/|accessdate=August 4, 2012|newspaper=Total Media Bridge|date=July 19, 2012}}</ref> In early September 2012, [[20th Century Fox]], the studio's new distributor, and DreamWorks Animation announced a release date of March 27, 2015, and a new pair of writers, [[Michael Colton]] and [[John Aboud]].<ref>{{cite press release|author1=DreamWorks Animation SKG, Inc.|title=New Distributor Twentieth Century Fox Unveils DreamWorks Animation's Release Slate Through 2016|url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/new-distributor-twentieth-century-fox-unveils-dreamworks-animations-release-slate-through-2016-169123176.html|publisher=PR Newswire|accessdate=December 10, 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006094204/http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/new-distributor-twentieth-century-fox-unveils-dreamworks-animations-release-slate-through-2016-169123176.html|archivedate=October 6, 2014|date=September 9, 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Benedict Cumberbatch]] and [[John Malkovich]] joined the cast in August 2013.<ref name=WrapCumberMalko>{{cite news|last=Sneider|first=Jeff|title=Benedict Cumberbatch, John Malkovich Join 'Penguins of Madagascar' (Exclusive)|url=https://www.thewrap.com/movies/column-post/benedict-cumberbatch-john-malkovich-join-penguins-madagascar-exclusive-108591|accessdate=August 6, 2013|newspaper=The Wrap|date=August 5, 2013}}</ref> Malkovich, who had been offered the role of Dr. Octavius Brine three and a half years before the film's release, told an audience at the July 2014 Comic-Con that he thought that it \"was a funny idea\" to use his voice for an octopus.<ref name=ColliderConRecap />\n\n==Release==\nOn May 20, 2014, the film's release date was moved back to November 26, 2014, from its initial March 27, 2015, date, switching places with DreamWorks Animation's other film ''[[Home (2015 animated film)|Home]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.deadline.com/2014/05/the-penguins-of-madagascar-release-date-home-dreamworks-animation/ |title=DreamWorks Animation Moves Up 'Penguins Of Madagascar' Bow, Bumps 'Home' To 2015 |work=Deadline.com |date=May 20, 2014 |accessdate=May 20, 2014}}</ref> [[Jeffrey Katzenberg]], DreamWorks Animation's CEO, reasoned that the film, coming from one of DWA's most successful franchises, would have an easier task to stand out around the [[Thanksgiving (United States)|Thanksgiving]] holiday season, while ''Home'' was to try to take advantage of a less competitive spring release window and repeat successful spring launches of some of DWA's original films including ''[[The Croods]]'' and ''[[How to Train Your Dragon (film)|How to Train Your Dragon]]''.<ref name=SAQ22014>{{cite web|title=DreamWorks Animation SKG's (DWA) CEO Jeffrey Katzenberg on Q2 2014 Results - Earnings Call Transcript|url=http://seekingalpha.com/article/2355535-dreamworks-animation-skgs-dwa-ceo-jeffrey-katzenberg-on-q2-2014-results-earnings-call-transcript?part=single|publisher=Seeking Alpha|accessdate=July 30, 2014|date=July 29, 2014}}</ref> The film was released two weeks earlier in China, on November 14, 2014.<ref name=DeadlineHitChina>{{cite web|last=Robb|first=David|url=https://deadline.com/2014/10/penguins-of-madagascar-will-hit-china-before-opening-stateside-857265/|title=\u2018Penguins Of Madagascar\u2019 Will Hit China Before Opening Stateside|date=October 21, 2014|work=Deadline|accessdate=October 22, 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe film was released in [[RealD 3D]] and [[Digital 3D]] formats.<ref name=YTTrailer1>{{cite web|author1=Moviefone|title=Penguins of Madagascar Trailer (2014): Benedict Cumberbatch, John Malkovich|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=N-SElhktQF0|publisher=YouTube|accessdate=June 13, 2014|date=June 11, 2014}}</ref> It was digitally remastered into the [[IMAX]] format, and released in select theaters across Europe, Asia, the Middle East and Latin America.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Vlessing|first1=Etan|title=Imax Signs Four-Picture Deal With 20th Century Fox|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/imax-signs-four-picture-deal-745177|accessdate=October 31, 2014|work=The Hollywood Reporter|date=October 30, 2014}}</ref> A four-issue comic book series based on the film was published by Titan Comics. Written by Alex Matthews and drawn by Lucas Fereyra.<ref>{{cite press release|title=Titan Announces New DreamWorks Animation \"Penguin of Madagascar\" Comic|url=http://www.comicbookresources.com/?page=article&id=55533|publisher=Comic Book Resources|accessdate=September 16, 2014|date=September 15, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Home media===\n''Penguins of Madagascar'' was released on DVD, Blu-ray and Blu-ray 3D on March 17, 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.comingsoon.net/movies/news/401391-dreamworks-penguins-of-madagascar-waddles-onto-blu-ray-and-dvd#/slide/1|title=DreamWorks' Penguins of Madagascar Waddles Onto Blu-ray and DVD - ComingSoon.net|work=ComingSoon.net|accessdate=January 21, 2015}}</ref> It topped the home video sales chart in its first week.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://variety.com/2015/film/news/penguins-of-madagascar-debuts-at-no-1-on-home-video-sales-chart-1201460321/|title=\u2018Penguins of Madagascar\u2019 Debuts at No. 1 on Home Video Sales Chart|author=Alex Stedman|magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=March 25, 2015|accessdate=March 26, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n\n===Box office===\n''Penguins of Madagascar'' grossed $83.4 million in North America and $290.2 million in foreign countries for a worldwide total of $373.6 million.<ref name=\"BOM\"/> The film's production budget was $132 million, which, according to the DreamWorks Animation's president Ann Dally, excluded \"[[Performance-related pay|incentive-based compensation]].\"<ref name=SAQ314Transcript /> By the end of 2014, the studio had to take a $57.1 million [[write-down]], primarily related to the performance of ''Penguins of Madagascar'' and another DreamWorks Animation film ''[[Mr. Peabody & Sherman]]''.<ref name=THR57MWriteDown>{{cite news|last1=Bond|first1=Paul|title=DreamWorks Animation Takes $57M Write-Down on 'Penguins of Madagascar'|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/dreamworks-animation-takes-57m-write-777474|accessdate=November 4, 2015|work=The Hollywood Reporter|date=February 24, 2015}}</ref><ref name=PRN4Q2014>{{cite press release|author1=DreamWorks Animation SKG|title=DreamWorks Animation Reports Fourth Quarter And Year-End 2014 Financial Results|url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/dreamworks-animation-reports-fourth-quarter-and-year-end-2014-financial-results-300040670.html|publisher=PR Newswire|accessdate=November 4, 2015|date=February 24, 2015}}</ref>\n\n''Penguins of Madagascar'' was released on November 26, 2014 in North America and Canada across 3,764 theatres. It earned $6.25 million on its opening day and $3.95 million the next day on [[Thanksgiving (United States)|Thanksgiving Day]].<ref>{{cite magazine | url = https://deadline.com/2014/11/mockingjay-penguins-of-madagascar-horrible-bosses-2-thanksgiving-box-office-1201299198/ | title = \u2018Mockingjay\u2019, \u2018Penguins\u2019 & \u2018Horrible Bosses 2\u2032 Cook Up T-Giving Box Office | author = Nancy Tartaglione | magazine = Deadline.com | date = November 27, 2014 | accessdate = November 28, 2014}}</ref> It earned $10.5 million [[Black Friday (shopping)|on Black Friday]].<ref>{{cite magazine | url = https://variety.com/2014/film/news/box-office-mockingjay-rules-black-friday-with-24-1-million-as-horrible-bosses-2-stumbles-1201366810/ | title = Box Office: \u2018Mockingjay\u2019 Rules Black Friday With $24.1 Million as \u2018Horrible Bosses 2\u2019 Stumbles | author = Maane Khatchatourian | magazine = Variety | date = November 19, 2014 | accessdate = November 30, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine | url = https://deadline.com/2014/11/hunger-games-box-office-thanksgiving-penguins-of-madgascar-horrible-bosses-2-1201301187/ | title = \u2018Mockingjay\u2019 Flies Away With Black Friday Cash; \u2018Penguins\u2019, \u2018Bosses\u2019 Left With Bones | author = Anthony D'Alessandro | magazine = Deadline.com | date = November 29, 2014 | accessdate = November 30, 2014}}</ref> The film underperformed during its opening weekend earning $25.4 million and debuting at #2 at the box office behind ''[[The Hunger Games: Mockingjay \u2013 Part 1]]'', for which 3D accounted for 24% of its opening-weekend gross.<ref>{{cite magazine | url = https://deadline.com/2014/11/hunger-games-box-office-thanksgiving-penguins-of-madgascar-horrible-bosses-2-1201301187/ | title = \u2018Mockingjay,\u2019 Holdovers Strong As Turkey Turnstiles Slow: Box Office | author = Anthony D'Alessandro | magazine = Deadline.com | date = November 30, 2014 |access-date= December 1, 2014}}</ref> The opening-weekend audience was evenly split among those under and over the age of 25, with 58% and female accounted 51%. In [[CinemaScore]] polls conducted during the opening weekend, cinema audiences gave ''Penguins of Madagascar'' an average grade of A- on an A+ to F scale.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.boxofficemojo.com/news/?id=3968&p=.htm | title = Weekend Report: \u2018Hunger Games\u2019 Devours Undercooked Franchise Titles Over Thanksgiving | author = Ray Subers | website = Box Office Mojo | date = November 30, 2014 | accessdate = December 29, 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe film was released in [[China]] on November 14,<ref name=DeadlineHitChina /> two weeks ahead of its North American debut, and earned $11.3 million from 3,500 screens, debuting at number two at the Chinese box office behind ''[[Interstellar (film)|Interstellar]]'' ($42 million).<ref>{{cite magazine | url = https://deadline.com/2014/11/international-box-office-interstellar-penguins-of-madagascar-china-dumb-and-dumber-to-big-hero-6-1201286020/ | title = \u2018Interstellar\u2019 Blasts Past $200M With $42M China Lift-Off: International Box Office | author = Nancy Tartaglione | magazine = Deadline.com | date = November 16, 2014 | accessdate = November 17, 2014}}</ref> In its opening weekend, the film earned $36.5 million from 47 markets.<ref name=\"1stweek\">{{cite web | url = https://www.boxofficemojo.com/news/?id=3969&p=.htm | title = Around-the-World Roundup: 'Mockingjay' Repeats, 'Interstellar' Nears $400 Million | author = Ray Subers | website = Box Office Mojo | date = November 30, 2014 | accessdate = December 19, 2014}}</ref> Overall, the top openings were in Russia ($8.2 million), Korea ($6 million), Italy ($4.63 million), Germany ($4.2 million), and Australia ($3.68 million).<ref name=\"Update\">{{cite web | url = https://deadline.com/2014/11/international-box-office-hunger-games-mockingjay-penguins-madagascar-paddington-horrible-bosses-interstellar-weekend-results-1201302872/ | title = \u2018Mockingjay\u2019, \u2018Interstellar\u2019, \u2018Penguins\u2019 Lead Frame; \u2018Paddington\u2019 Charms UK: Int\u2019l B.O. Update | author = Nancy Tartaglione | date = November 30, 2014 | accessdate = December 1, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"$500million\">{{cite magazine | url = https://deadline.com/2015/01/international-box-office-hobbit-taken-3-american-sniper-pk-angel-of-death-1201340651/ | title = \u2018Hobbit\u2019 Passes $500M; \u2018American Sniper\u2019, \u2018Taken 3\u2032 Skillful: Intl Box Office Update | author = Nancy Tartaglione | magazine = Deadline.com | date = January 4, 2015 | accessdate = January 5, 2015}}</ref> The film's opening in Germany was the second-highest for an animated film in 2014, behind ''[[How to Train Your Dragon 2]]''.<ref name=\"Update\"/>\n\n===Critical response===\nThe film has a 73% rating on [[Rotten Tomatoes]] based on 110 reviews, with an average rating of 6.2/10. The site's consensus was \"''Penguins of Madagascar'' is fast and brightly colored enough to entertain small children, but too frantically silly to offer real filmgoing fun for the whole family.\"<ref>{{cite web | url= https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/penguins_of_madagascar/ | title=Penguins of Madagascar | work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] | publisher=[[Fandango Media]] | access-date= January 19, 2019 }}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the film achieved a score of 53 out of 100 based on reviews from 31 critics, indicating \"mixed or average reviews\".<ref>{{cite web | url= https://www.metacritic.com/movie/penguins-of-madagascar | title=Penguins of Madagascar Reviews | work=[[Metacritic]] | publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] | access-date=July 11, 2015}}</ref> Audiences surveyed by [[CinemaScore]] gave the film a grade A\u2013.<ref>https://www.cinemascore.com/publicsearch/index/title/ </ref>\n\nMichael Rechtshaffen of ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' gave the film a negative review, saying \"While there are plenty of madcap antics to fill a feature, all that manic energy ultimately proves to be more exhausting than exhilarating.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/penguins-madagascar-film-review-748219|title='Penguins of Madagascar': Film Review|author=Michael Rechtshaffen|work=The Hollywood Reporter|accessdate=November 26, 2014}}</ref> Elizabeth Weitzman of the ''[[New York Daily News]]'' gave the film three out of five stars, saying \"Granted, it's no classic, but a sassy script and good-natured voice work from Benedict Cumberbatch and John Malkovich should keep kids and grownups entertained over the holidays.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/movies/penguins-madagascar-movie-review-article-1.2022223|title=\u2018Penguins of Madagascar,\u2019 movie review|work=NY Daily News|accessdate=November 26, 2014}}</ref> Ignatiy Vishnevetsky of ''[[The A.V. Club]]'' gave the film a B, saying \"Frenetic and frequently funny, ''Penguins Of Madagascar'' represents the DreamWorks Animation franchise style\u2014which boils down to self-aware, but na\u00efve, talking animals who learn kid-friendly life lessons\u2014at its most palatable.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.avclub.com/review/penguins-madagascar-dreamworks-animation-its-most--212233|title=Review: Penguins Of Madagascar is DreamWorks Animation at its most amusingly energetic |newspaper=[[The A.V. Club]]|accessdate=November 26, 2014}}</ref> Ben Kenigsberg of ''[[The New York Times]]'' gave the film a positive review, saying \"The lack of originality is offset by sheer silliness, including Classified and Skipper's Abbott and Costello-style argument over whether there's a long I in 'diversion.' The word fits the movie.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/11/26/movies/penguins-of-madagascar-with-voice-of-benedict-cumberbatch.html?partner=rss&emc=rss|title=\u2018Penguins of Madagascar,\u2019 With Voice of Benedict Cumberbatch|author=Ben Kenigsberg|work=The New York Times|accessdate=November 26, 2014}}</ref>\n\nBill Zwecker of the ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'' gave the film three out of four stars, saying \"Once again the ''Madagascar'' team have come up with a winner&nbsp;\u2013 a nice way to kick off the Thanksgiving and holiday filmgoing experience for the whole family.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://entertainment.suntimes.com/movies/penguins-madagascar-happy-feat-action-comedy/|title=\u2018Penguins of Madagascar': A happy feat of action, comedy|work=Chicago Sun-Times|accessdate=November 26, 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141208042813/http://entertainment.suntimes.com/movies/penguins-madagascar-happy-feat-action-comedy/|archivedate=December 8, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Lou Lumenick of the ''[[New York Post]]'' gave the film one out of four stars, saying ''\"Penguins of Madagascar'' is a lazy, noisy ADHD-addled collection of animated clich\u00e9s guaranteed to give anyone older than 5 a headache, even if you don't see it in optional 3-D.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2014/11/25/penguins-of-madagascar-stinks-on-and-off-ice/|title=\u2018Penguins of Madagascar\u2019 stinks on (and off) ice |work=New York Post|accessdate=November 26, 2014}}</ref> Jeff Labrecque of ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' gave the film a C-, saying \"''Penguins of Madagascar'' aims primarily for the kiddies, racing from one frenetic action sequence to another like some haywire Walter Lantz cartoon.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,20876861,00.html|title=Penguins of Madagascar Review - Movie Reviews and News - EW.com|work=EW.com|accessdate=November 26, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Awards and nominations===\n{| class=wikitable style=text-align:center\n|-\n! colspan=4 style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | List of awards and nominations\n|-\n! style=\"background:#ccc|Award/Film Festival\n! style=\"background:#ccc|Category\n! style=\"background:#ccc|Recipient(s)\n! style=\"background:#ccc|Result\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\"|[[42nd Annie Awards]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2014/12/annie-awards-nominations-big-hero-six-lego-movie-full-list-1201304339/|title=Annie Awards Nominations Unveiled|website=Deadline|date=December 1, 2014|first=Patrick|last=Hipes|accessdate=June 22, 2015}}</ref>\n| Outstanding Achievement for Animated Effects in an Animated Production\n| Mitul Patel, Nicolas Delbecq, Santosh Khedkar and Yash Argawal\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Outstanding Achievement for Character Animation in an Animated Feature Production\n| Ravi Kamble\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Outstanding Achievement for Character Design in an Animated Feature Production\n| Craig Kellman, Joe Moshier, Stevie Lewis and Todd Kurosawa\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n|[[Cinema Audio Society Awards|51st Cinema Audio Society Awards]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2015/01/cas-awards-nominations-2015-guardians-of-the-galaxy-nominees-1201348559/|title=CAS Awards Nominees Sound Familiar \u2013 But Not All Of Them|date=January 13, 2015|website=Deadline|accessdate=June 22, 2015}}</ref>\n|Outstanding Achievement in Sound Mixing for Motion Picture - Animated\n|Tighe Sheldon, Paul N.J. Ottosson, Dennis Sands and Randy K. Singer\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|[[2015 Kids' Choice Awards|28th Kids' Choice Awards]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ibtimes.com/kids-choice-awards-nominees-2015-nominations-refresher-list-march-28-award-show-1861866|title=Kids\u2019 Choice Awards Nominees 2015: A Nominations Refresher List Before The March 28 Award Show|date=March 27, 2015|work=[[International Business Times]]|accessdate=March 29, 2015}}</ref>\n|Favorite Animated Movie\n|rowspan=2|[[Eric Darnell]] and [[Simon J. Smith]]\n|{{Nom}}\n|-\n|[[St. Louis Gateway Film Critics Association|11th St. Louis Film Critics Association Awards]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.awardsdaily.com/blog/2014/12/st-louis-film-critic-nominees/|title=St Louis Film Critic Nominees|first=Ryan|last=Adams|date=December 11, 2014|website=Awards Daily|accessdate=June 22, 2015}}</ref>\n|[[St. Louis Gateway Film Critics Association Award for Best Animated Film|Best Animated Film]]\n|{{nom}}\n|}\n\n==Soundtrack==\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Penguins of Madagascar: Music from the Motion Picture\n| type       = film\n| artist     = [[Lorne Balfe]]\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| released   = {{Start date|2014|11|25}}\n| recorded   = 2014\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Film score]]\n| length     = 52:46\n| label      = [[Relativity Music Group]]\n| producer   = [[Hans Zimmer]]\n| chronology = [[DreamWorks Animation]]\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n| misc       = {{Extra chronology\n | artist     = [[DreamWorks Animation]]\n | type       = film\n | prev_title = [[How to Train Your Dragon 2]]\n | prev_year  = 2014\n | title      = Penguins of Madagascar\n | year       = 2014\n | next_title =\n | next_year  =\n}}\n}}\n[[Lorne Balfe]] composed the original score for the film,<ref name=FMRSoundtrack /> making it his first solo debut in a DreamWorks Animation film. Balfe wrote the additional music for the previous two ''[[Madagascar (franchise)|Madagascar]]'' films and helped ''Madagascar'' composer [[Hans Zimmer]] with the score for ''[[Megamind]]''. The soundtrack was released on November 25, 2014, by [[Relativity Media|Relativity Music Group]].<ref name=FMRSoundtrack>{{cite web|title=\u2018Penguins of Madagascar\u2019 Soundtrack Announced|url=http://filmmusicreporter.com/2014/11/13/penguins-of-madagascar-soundtrack-announced/|publisher=Film Music Reporter|accessdate=November 15, 2014|date=November 13, 2014}}</ref> Relativity also released an [[Extended play|EP]], ''Penguins of Madagascar: Black & White Christmas Album'', which featured five holiday songs.<ref name=FMRSoundtrack />\n\n{{Track listing\n| total_length = \n| title1       = The Penguins of Madagascar\n| length1      = 4:10 \n| title2       = Antarctica\n| length2      = 3:31 \n| title3       = Demersus\n| length3      = 2:53 \n| title4       = Sclateri\n| length4      = 3:25 \n| title5       = Adeliae\n| length5      = 3:31 \n| title6       = Forsteri\n| length6      = 2:52 \n| title7       = Patagonicus\n| length7      = 3:03\n| title8       = Magellanicus\n| length8      = 1:24 \n| title9       = Private\u2019s Theme\n| length9      = 2:34 \n| title10      = Robustus\n| length10     = 3:36 \n| title11      = Eudyptula Minor\n| length11     = 1:35 \n| title12      = Chrysolophus\n| length12     = 2:51 \n| title13      = Chrysocome\n| length13     = 1:59 \t\n| title14      = Antipodes\n| length14     = 1:20 \n| title15      = Schlegeli\n| length15     = 2:46 \t\n| title16      = Mendiculus\n| length16     = 3:14 \n| title17      = Papua\n| length17     = 1:56 \n| title18      = Humboldti\n| length18     = 2:52 \n| title19      = He Is Dave\n| note19       = featuring [[Antony Genn]]\n| length19     = 3:14 \n}}\n\n==Video game==\nA video game based on the film, titled ''Penguins of Madagascar'', and published by Little Orbit, was released on November 25, 2014 for [[Nintendo 3DS]], [[Wii]], and [[Wii U]].<ref>{{cite press release|title=Smile and Wave, Boys! Little Orbit Announces Penguins of Madagascar Video Game|url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/smile-and-wave-boys-little-orbit-announces-penguins-of-madagascar-video-game-274336461.html|publisher=PR Newswire|accessdate=September 11, 2014|date=September 8, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* {{Official website|http://madagascar.dreamworks.com/movies/penguins-of-madagascar}}\n* {{IMDb title|1911658}}\n* {{mojo title|penguinsofmadagascar}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes|the_penguins_of_madagascar}}\n* {{metacritic film|penguins-of-madagascar}}\n\n{{Madagascar (franchise)}}\n{{DreamWorks Animation}}\n{{Eric Darnell}}\n{{Simon J. Smith}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Penguins Of Madagascar, The (film)}}\n[[Category:2014 films]]\n[[Category:2014 3D films]]\n[[Category:3D animated films]]\n[[Category:2014 computer-animated films]]\n[[Category:2010s action films]]\n[[Category:2010s adventure films]]\n[[Category:2010s American animated films]]\n[[Category:2010s children's comedy films]]\n[[Category:20th Century Fox animated films]]\n[[Category:20th Century Fox films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:Madagascar (franchise) films]]\n[[Category:American 3D films]]\n[[Category:American action comedy films]]\n[[Category:American children's animated comedy films]]\n[[Category:American computer-animated films]]\n[[Category:Animated action films]]\n[[Category:Animated films about penguins]]\n[[Category:Animated films about wolves]]\n[[Category:DreamWorks Animation animated films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Film spin-offs]]\n[[Category:Films about polar bears]]\n[[Category:Films featuring anthropomorphic characters]]\n[[Category:Films set in Shanghai]]\n[[Category:Films set in New York City]]\n[[Category:Films set in Venice]]\n[[Category:Films set in zoos]]\n[[Category:IMAX films]]\n[[Category:2010s spy comedy films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Eric Darnell]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Simon J. Smith]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Lorne Balfe]]\n[[Category:2010s action comedy films]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the animated feature film|the Nickelodeon TV series|The Penguins of Madagascar}}\n{{Use American English|date=August 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name        = Penguins of Madagascar\n| image       = Penguins of Madagascar poster.jpg\n| alt         =\n| caption     = Theatrical release poster\n| director    = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Eric Darnell]]\n* [[Simon J. Smith]]\n}}\n| producer    = {{Plainlist|\n* Mark Swift\n* [[Lara Breay]]<ref name=WrapCumberMalko />\n* Tripp Hudson<ref>{{cite web|first1=Mike|last=Milo|title=News: THE PENGUINS OF MADAGASCAR &#124; Official Trailer Revealed!|url=http://www.animationinsider.com/2014/06/news-the-penguins-of-madagascar-official-trailer-revealed/|publisher=Animation Insider|accessdate=June 13, 2014|date=June 11, 2014}}</ref>\n}}\n| screenplay  = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Michael Colton]]<ref name=DWAPOM />\n* [[John Aboud]]<ref name=DWAPOM />\n* Brandon Sawyer<ref name=DWAPOM>{{cite web|title=Penguins of Madagascar|url=http://madagascar.dreamworks.com/movies/penguins-of-madagascar|publisher=DreamWorks Animation|accessdate=September 26, 2014}}</ref>\n}}\n| story       = {{Plainlist|\n* Alan J. Schoolcraft\n* Brent Simons\n* Michael Colton\n* John Aboud\n}}\n| based on    = {{Based on|Characters created|[[Tom McGrath (animator)|Tom McGrath]]|Eric Darnell}}\n| starring    = {{Plainlist|\n* Tom McGrath\n* [[Chris Miller (animator)|Chris Miller]]\n* [[Christopher Knights]]\n* [[Conrad Vernon]]\n* [[Benedict Cumberbatch]]\n* [[Ken Jeong]]\n* [[Annet Mahendru]]\n* [[Peter Stormare]]\n* [[John Malkovich]]\n}}\n| music       = [[Lorne Balfe]]<ref name=score>{{cite news|title=Lorne Balfe to Score \u2018The Penguins of Madagascar\u2019|url=http://filmmusicreporter.com/2014/01/08/lorne-balfe-to-score-the-penguins-of-madagascar/|accessdate=January 19, 2014|newspaper=Film Music Reporter|date=January 8, 2014}}</ref><ref>[http://new.pitchengine.com/pitches/54e137a7-f032-4b04-bd98-f2dcc2fae21d Dreamworks Animation : High-Fives All Around: The Penguins Of Madagascar Recruited For Top-Secret Assignment This Fall<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n| editing     = Nick Kenway\n| studio      = [[DreamWorks Animation]]<br />[[Pacific Data Images]]<ref name=YTTrailer1 />\n| distributor = [[20th Century Fox]]\n| released    = {{Film date|2014|11|14|China|2014|11|26|United States}}\n| runtime     = 92 minutes<!--Theatrical runtime: 91:42--><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/penguins-madagascar-film-0 | title=''PENGUINS OF MADAGASCAR'' (U) | work=[[British Board of Film Classification]] | date=November 6, 2014 | accessdate=November 6, 2014}}</ref>\n| country     = United States\n| language    = English\n| budget      = $132 million<ref name=SAQ314Transcript>{{cite web|title=DreamWorks Animation SKG's (DWA) CEO Jeffrey Katzenberg on Q3 2014 Results - Earnings Call Transcript|url=http://seekingalpha.com/article/2613945-dreamworks-animation-skgs-dwa-ceo-jeffrey-katzenberg-on-q3-2014-results-earnings-call-transcript?part=single|publisher=Seeking Alpha|accessdate=October 30, 2014|date=October 29, 2014|quote=...our next 2 movies, Penguins of Madagascar and Home, have production budgets of $132 million each, excluding incentive-based compensation.}}</ref>\n| gross       = $373 million<ref name=\"BOM\">{{cite web |url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=penguinsofmadagascar.htm |title=Penguins of Madagascar (2014) |website=Box Office Mojo |accessdate=November 10, 2015}}</ref>\n}}\n'''''Penguins of Madagascar''''', released on home video as '''''Penguins of Madagascar: The Movie''''', is a 2014 American [[Computer animation|computer-animated]] [[Spy film|spy]] [[Action film|action]] [[comedy film]]<ref name=DWAStarsAlign /> produced by [[DreamWorks Animation]] and distributed by [[20th Century Fox]]. It is a spin-off of the [[Madagascar (franchise)|''Madagascar'']] film series, and takes place right after the events of ''[[Madagascar 3: Europe's Most Wanted]]'',<ref name=ColliderHomePenguinsNYCC>{{cite web|last1=Nemiroff|first1=Perri|title=HOME and PENGUINS OF MADAGASCAR Comic-Con Panel Recap: New Footage, Evil Scientist Octopus, 28-Second Alien Invasion and More|url=https://collider.com/penguins-of-madagascar-comic-con-panel-recap-home/|publisher=Collider.com|accessdate=October 14, 2014|date=October 12, 2014}}</ref> following the [[penguin]]s Skipper, Kowalski, Rico and Private in their own adventure.<ref name=DWAStarsAlign>{{cite news|title=The Stars Align For 2015 DreamWorks Animation Films|url=http://new.pitchengine.com/pitches/9478b619-99eb-433c-b1e3-41579d15230a|accessdate=January 19, 2014|newspaper=Pitch Engine|date=August 15, 2013|author=DreamWorks Animation}}</ref> Apart from the main characters, it is unrelated to the [[The Penguins of Madagascar|TV series of the same name]].<ref name=ColliderConRecap>{{cite web|last1=Goldberg|first1=Matt|title=PENGUINS OF MADAGASCAR Comic-Con Panel Recap: A Great DreamWorks Animated Film Might Be on the Way|url=https://collider.com/penguins-of-madagascar-comic-con-panel-recap/|publisher=Collider.com|accessdate=July 25, 2014|date=July 24, 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe film was directed by [[Simon J. Smith]] and [[Eric Darnell]],<ref name=WrapDateSwitch /> and written by [[Michael Colton]], [[John Aboud]],<ref name=WrapCumberMalko /> and Brandon Sawyer.<ref name=DWAPOM /> It stars the voices of [[Tom McGrath (animator)|Tom McGrath]], [[Chris Miller (animator)|Chris Miller]], [[Conrad Vernon]], [[Christopher Knights]], [[Benedict Cumberbatch]], [[John Malkovich]], and [[Ken Jeong]]. The film was released on November 26, 2014.<ref name=WrapCumberMalko /> It is the first and only film in the ''Madagascar'' franchise that was distributed by 20th Century Fox and was the final DreamWorks Animation film produced by [[Pacific Data Images]] before its closure on January 22, 2015.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Wolfe|first1=Jennifer|title=DreamWorks Animation Shuttering PDI|url=http://www.awn.com/news/dreamworks-animation-shuttering-pdi|publisher=Animation World Network|accessdate=March 20, 2015|date=January 22, 2015}}</ref> Despite taking a gross of $373 million on a $132 million budget, the film [[Box office bomb|underperformed at the box office]] and forced a [[write-down]] for the studio.<ref name=THR57MWriteDown />\n\n==Plot==\nIn [[Antarctica]], three young penguin brothers \u2014 Skipper, Kowalski, and Rico \u2014 defy the laws of nature in order to save an egg the other penguins believe to be doomed. After saving it from a pack of [[leopard seals]] on an abandoned ship, and accidentally setting themselves adrift on an iceberg, the egg hatches into their new member, Private, (before the events of the [[Madagascar (2005 film)|first film]]).\n\nTen years later (after the events of the [[Madagascar 3: Europe's Most Wanted|previous film]]), the penguins decide to leave the circus to celebrate Private's birthday by breaking into [[United States Bullion Depository|Fort Knox]] in order to treat him to a discontinued snack called \"Cheezy Dibbles\" in the vending machine of their break room. Despite this, Private begins to feel out of place with the team, as he is constantly described as being the \"secretary/mascot\".\n\nSuddenly, they are abducted by the machine and sent to [[Venice]], [[Italy]] by Dr. Octavius Brine, a renowned geneticist who reveals he is actually an octopus named Dave, who has grown resentful of penguins after their cuteness had him shunned from every zoo and aquarium across the globe. Rico swallows Dave's collection of [[snowglobes]] along with a canister of a green substance called the Medusa Serum before the four escape and are chased through the canals and streets of Venice by Dave's henchmen.\n\nWhen cornered, they are rescued by a group of animals from an [[Arctic]] elite undercover inter-species task force agency called \"The North Wind\" consisting of their leader, a [[wolf]] whose name is classified in which Skipper mistakenly calls him \"Classified\" throughout this film, a [[harp seal]] demolitionist named Short Fuse, a [[polar bear]] named Corporal, and an intelligent [[snowy owl]] named Eva, who Kowalski instantly falls in love with. Their mission is to help animals who can't help themselves and have been fighting Dave to protect the penguin population.\n\nAt their hideout, their communication systems are hacked by Dave, who reveals that he has an enormous supply of the Medusa Serum and that he intends to capture the penguins out of every zoo he was kicked out of. Viewing the penguins as a hindrance to their mission, Classified tranquilizes the group and sends them to their most remote base (which happens to be on [[Madagascar]]) but the penguins awaken mid-flight and crash land in the [[Sahara Desert]] before making their way to [[Shanghai, China]], which they mistake for [[Dublin, Ireland]]. Discovering Dave's next target in Shanghai using Dave's snowglobe collection, the penguins ship themselves to the same current location and make their way to the zoo. Skipper disguises Private as a mermaid-tailed penguin (a tourist attraction) to distract Dave from his real target, but Private is captured along with the Shanghai penguins after the North Wind arrives to put a stop to Dave's plan. The penguins take the North Wind's high-tech plane to give chase, but inadvertently self-destruct the machine. They manage to track Private to an island base, using a tracking device planted on him when Classified darted them before planting them in a flight to Madagascar. \n\nMeanwhile, on the island, Dave demonstrates his way to use the medusa serum to genetically mutate the penguins into hideous monsters as an effort to make humans disgusted by them as revenge. Skipper and Classified argue on the best means to rescue the captives and stop Dave, finally settling on Classified's plan of a frontal assault and Skipper agrees to act as a diversion. The North Wind manages to corner Dave in his lair only to be captured by Dave's henchmen as well as the other penguins. Dave demonstrates his mutation ray at full power on Private, apparently disintegrating him with the beam, but unbeknownst to them he escapes at the last minute by using a paper clip he swallowed earlier. Private rescues the North Wind members, who want to [[tactical formation|regroup]] due to lack of equipment, but Private, not wanting to leave anyone behind goes to stop Dave. As Dave's submarine docks at [[New York City|New York]] with the promise of returning the penguins he found to the zoo, he turns the ray on the rest of the penguins, mutating them all into hideous monsters. The city erupts into chaos as the brainwashed, mutated penguins run amok on the terrified human crowd. Getting Skipper, Kowalski and Rico back to their senses, Private decides to connect himself into the ray to return them to normal. After fending off Dave and his henchman, they manage to turn all the penguins back to normal in one huge blast.\n\nPrivate is left partially mutated from the machine while the rest of the penguins are restored to normal. Despite his strange new look, the Penguins show their gratitude and new-found respect for Private. Dave (who was caught in the blast) has been turned into a pipsqueak version of himself and is trapped in a snow globe where he is admired by a little girl. Finally seeing one another as equals, Classified promises to grant the Penguins anything they want. In addition to Kowalski getting a kiss from Eva, the Penguins are given their own jet packs and they then fly off above the clouds looking for their new adventures.\n\nIn a [[mid-credits scene]], the Penguins return to the circus and plug Mort into the ray and use him to revert Private back to normal. Mort does not appear to show any side effects from the ray until he manages to swallow King Julien whole, much to the latter's amusement.\n\n==Voice cast==\n{{See also|List of Madagascar (franchise) characters}}\n[[File:John Malkovich & Benedict Cumberbatch, Penguins of Madagascar, SDCC 2014.jpg|thumb|[[John Malkovich]] and [[Benedict Cumberbatch]] talking at the ''Penguins of Madagascar'' panel at the 2014 [[San Diego Comic-Con International]]]]\n* [[Tom McGrath (animator)|Tom McGrath]] as Skipper, the leader of the [[penguin]]s.<ref name=USATPeek>{{cite news|last1=Truitt|first1=Brian|title=Sneak Peek: 'Penguins of Madagascar'|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/movies/2014/06/08/penguins-of-madagascar-first-look/9727597/|accessdate=June 9, 2014|work=USA Today|date=June 8, 2014}}</ref>\n* [[Chris Miller (animator)|Chris Miller]] as Kowalski, the brains of the penguins.<ref name=USATPeek />\n* [[Christopher Knights]] as Private, the rookie of the penguins.<ref name=USATPeek />\n* [[Conrad Vernon]] as Rico,<ref name=VarietyReview>{{cite news|last1=Berkshire|first1=Geoff|title=Film Review: \u2018Penguins of Madagascar\u2019|url=https://variety.com/2014/film/reviews/film-review-penguins-of-madagascar-1201353894/|accessdate=November 12, 2014|work=Variety|date=November 12, 2014}}</ref> the loose cannon of the penguins.\n* [[Benedict Cumberbatch]] as Classified, a British [[wolf]] and team leader of the North Wind.<ref name=WrapCumberMalko /><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2014/jun/11/benedict-cumberbatch-penguins-of-madagascar |title=Benedict Cumberbatch to voice wolf in new Madagascar movie |first=Ben |last=Beaumont-Thomas |date=June 11, 2014|publisher=The Guardian|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.vox.com/2014/11/26/7290373/benedict-cumberbatch-penguins |title=Here are some of Benedict Cumberbatch\u2019s most oddly sexy lines from Penguins of Madagascar |first=Emily Todd |last=VanDerWerff |date=November 26, 2014 |website=Vox}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cartoonbrew.com/feature-film/penguins-of-madagascar-actor-benedict-cumberbatch-thinks-he-worked-on-a-disney-film-105013.html |title=Benedict Cumberbatch Thinks 'Penguins of Madagascar' is A Disney Film |date=October 24, 2014 |website=Cartoon Brew}}</ref>\n* [[Ken Jeong]] as Short Fuse, a Belgian explosive and demolitions expert [[harp seal]] and a member of the North Wind.<ref name=WrapDateSwitch>{{cite web|last=Cunningham|first=Todd|title=DreamWorks Animation Switches Release Dates on \u2018Penguins of Madagascar\u2019 and \u2018Home\u2019|url=https://www.thewrap.com/dreamworks-animation-switches-release-dates-on-penguins-of-madagascar-and-home/|publisher=The Wrap|accessdate=May 21, 2014|date=May 20, 2014}}</ref>\n* [[Annet Mahendru]] as Eva, a Russian [[snowy owl]], Kowalski's love interest, and the north wind's intelligence analyst.<ref name=\"USATPeek\" />\n* [[Peter Stormare]] as Corporal, a Norwegian [[polar bear]] and a member of the North Wind who serves as the muscle.<ref name=USATPeek />\n* [[John Malkovich]] as Dave, a villainous and disgruntled [[octopus]] who has the human disguise of Dr. Octavius Brine.<ref name=\"WrapCumberMalko\" /><ref name=\"USATPeek\" /><ref name=\"EWTralierSpies\">{{cite news|last1=McHenry|first1=Jackson|title='The Penguins of Madagascar' trailer: Spies and Benedict Cumberbatch -- VIDEO|url=http://insidemovies.ew.com/2014/06/11/penguins-madagascar-benedict-cumberbatch/|accessdate=June 13, 2014|work=Entertainment Weekly|date=June 11, 2014}}</ref>\n* [[Werner Herzog]] as a documentary filmmaker.<ref name=SlashFilmRecap>{{cite web|last1=Han|first1=Angie|title=Penguins of Madagascar\u2019 Footage Recap and Panel Highlights [Comic Con 2014]|url=https://www.slashfilm.com/penguins-of-madagascar-footage-comic-con/|publisher=/Film|accessdate=July 25, 2014|date=July 25, 2014}}</ref>\n* [[Danny Jacobs (actor)|Danny Jacobs]] as King Julien XIII, a [[ring-tailed lemur]].\n* [[Andy Richter]] as Mort, a [[Goodman's mouse lemur]].\n\n==Production==\nA [[direct-to-video]] film featuring the penguins had been in the works since 2005 when the first ''[[Madagascar (2005 film)|Madagascar]]'' film was released, with a release date initially planned for 2009.<ref>{{cite news|last=Fritz|first=Ben|title=D'Works will rely on animal instinct|url=https://www.variety.com/article/VR1117929100|accessdate=October 27, 2011|newspaper=Variety|date=September 14, 2005}}</ref> The studio announced in March 2011 that the penguin characters would be given their own feature film to be directed by [[Simon J. Smith]], the co-director of ''[[Bee Movie]]'', produced by [[Lara Breay]], and written by Alan J. Schoolcraft and Brent Simons, the writers of DreamWorks' ''[[Megamind]]''.<ref>{{cite news | last=Kit | first=Borys | url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/madagascar-spin-be-helmed-by-222257 | title='Madagascar' Spin-Off to Be Helmed by 'Bee Movie' Co-Director (Exclusive) | work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=August 11, 2011 | accessdate=August 12, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/dreamworks-developing-madagascar-penguins-spinoff-172353|title=DreamWorks Developing 'Madagascar' Penguins Spinoff Movie (Exclusive) |last=Kit |first=Borys |work=HollywoodReporter.com |date=March 29, 2011 |accessdate=March 31, 2011}}</ref>\n\nAt the July 2012 [[San Diego Comic-Con International|Comic-Con]], DreamWorks Animation announced that the film, titled ''The Penguins of Madagascar'', would be released in 2015.<ref>{{cite news|last=B. Vary|first=Adam|title=DreamWorks Animation Comic-Con panel: Caveman families and penguin movies!|url=http://insidemovies.ew.com/2012/07/12/dreamworks-animation-comic-con-panel/|accessdate=July 13, 2012|newspaper=Entertainment Weekly|date=July 12, 2012}}</ref> [[Bob Schooley|Robert Schooley]], one of the producers of ''The Penguins'' series, said that the film would be unrelated to the TV series of the same name, but added that that could always change.<ref>{{cite news|title=Email Interview With Robert Schooley|url=http://www.totalmediabridge.com/email-interview-with-robert-schooley/|accessdate=August 4, 2012|newspaper=Total Media Bridge|date=July 19, 2012}}</ref> In early September 2012, [[20th Century Fox]], the studio's new distributor, and DreamWorks Animation announced a release date of March 27, 2015, and a new pair of writers, [[Michael Colton]] and [[John Aboud]].<ref>{{cite press release|author1=DreamWorks Animation SKG, Inc.|title=New Distributor Twentieth Century Fox Unveils DreamWorks Animation's Release Slate Through 2016|url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/new-distributor-twentieth-century-fox-unveils-dreamworks-animations-release-slate-through-2016-169123176.html|publisher=PR Newswire|accessdate=December 10, 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006094204/http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/new-distributor-twentieth-century-fox-unveils-dreamworks-animations-release-slate-through-2016-169123176.html|archivedate=October 6, 2014|date=September 9, 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Benedict Cumberbatch]] and [[John Malkovich]] joined the cast in August 2013.<ref name=WrapCumberMalko>{{cite news|last=Sneider|first=Jeff|title=Benedict Cumberbatch, John Malkovich Join 'Penguins of Madagascar' (Exclusive)|url=https://www.thewrap.com/movies/column-post/benedict-cumberbatch-john-malkovich-join-penguins-madagascar-exclusive-108591|accessdate=August 6, 2013|newspaper=The Wrap|date=August 5, 2013}}</ref> Malkovich, who had been offered the role of Dr. Octavius Brine three and a half years before the film's release, told an audience at the July 2014 Comic-Con that he thought that it \"was a funny idea\" to use his voice for an octopus.<ref name=ColliderConRecap />\n\n==Release==\nOn May 20, 2014, the film's release date was moved back to November 26, 2014, from its initial March 27, 2015, date, switching places with DreamWorks Animation's other film ''[[Home (2015 animated film)|Home]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.deadline.com/2014/05/the-penguins-of-madagascar-release-date-home-dreamworks-animation/ |title=DreamWorks Animation Moves Up 'Penguins Of Madagascar' Bow, Bumps 'Home' To 2015 |work=Deadline.com |date=May 20, 2014 |accessdate=May 20, 2014}}</ref> [[Jeffrey Katzenberg]], DreamWorks Animation's CEO, reasoned that the film, coming from one of DWA's most successful franchises, would have an easier task to stand out around the [[Thanksgiving (United States)|Thanksgiving]] holiday season, while ''Home'' was to try to take advantage of a less competitive spring release window and repeat successful spring launches of some of DWA's original films including ''[[The Croods]]'' and ''[[How to Train Your Dragon (film)|How to Train Your Dragon]]''.<ref name=SAQ22014>{{cite web|title=DreamWorks Animation SKG's (DWA) CEO Jeffrey Katzenberg on Q2 2014 Results - Earnings Call Transcript|url=http://seekingalpha.com/article/2355535-dreamworks-animation-skgs-dwa-ceo-jeffrey-katzenberg-on-q2-2014-results-earnings-call-transcript?part=single|publisher=Seeking Alpha|accessdate=July 30, 2014|date=July 29, 2014}}</ref> The film was released two weeks earlier in China, on November 14, 2014.<ref name=DeadlineHitChina>{{cite web|last=Robb|first=David|url=https://deadline.com/2014/10/penguins-of-madagascar-will-hit-china-before-opening-stateside-857265/|title=\u2018Penguins Of Madagascar\u2019 Will Hit China Before Opening Stateside|date=October 21, 2014|work=Deadline|accessdate=October 22, 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe film was released in [[RealD 3D]] and [[Digital 3D]] formats.<ref name=YTTrailer1>{{cite web|author1=Moviefone|title=Penguins of Madagascar Trailer (2014): Benedict Cumberbatch, John Malkovich|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=N-SElhktQF0|publisher=YouTube|accessdate=June 13, 2014|date=June 11, 2014}}</ref> It was digitally remastered into the [[IMAX]] format, and released in select theaters across Europe, Asia, the Middle East and Latin America.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Vlessing|first1=Etan|title=Imax Signs Four-Picture Deal With 20th Century Fox|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/imax-signs-four-picture-deal-745177|accessdate=October 31, 2014|work=The Hollywood Reporter|date=October 30, 2014}}</ref> A four-issue comic book series based on the film was published by Titan Comics. Written by Alex Matthews and drawn by Lucas Fereyra.<ref>{{cite press release|title=Titan Announces New DreamWorks Animation \"Penguin of Madagascar\" Comic|url=http://www.comicbookresources.com/?page=article&id=55533|publisher=Comic Book Resources|accessdate=September 16, 2014|date=September 15, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Home media===\n''Penguins of Madagascar'' was released on DVD, Blu-ray and Blu-ray 3D on March 17, 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.comingsoon.net/movies/news/401391-dreamworks-penguins-of-madagascar-waddles-onto-blu-ray-and-dvd#/slide/1|title=DreamWorks' Penguins of Madagascar Waddles Onto Blu-ray and DVD - ComingSoon.net|work=ComingSoon.net|accessdate=January 21, 2015}}</ref> It topped the home video sales chart in its first week.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://variety.com/2015/film/news/penguins-of-madagascar-debuts-at-no-1-on-home-video-sales-chart-1201460321/|title=\u2018Penguins of Madagascar\u2019 Debuts at No. 1 on Home Video Sales Chart|author=Alex Stedman|magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=March 25, 2015|accessdate=March 26, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n\n===Box office===\n''Penguins of Madagascar'' grossed $83.4 million in North America and $290.2 million in foreign countries for a worldwide total of $373.6 million.<ref name=\"BOM\"/> The film's production budget was $132 million, which, according to the DreamWorks Animation's president Ann Dally, excluded \"[[Performance-related pay|incentive-based compensation]].\"<ref name=SAQ314Transcript /> By the end of 2014, the studio had to take a $57.1 million [[write-down]], primarily related to the performance of ''Penguins of Madagascar'' and another DreamWorks Animation film ''[[Mr. Peabody & Sherman]]''.<ref name=THR57MWriteDown>{{cite news|last1=Bond|first1=Paul|title=DreamWorks Animation Takes $57M Write-Down on 'Penguins of Madagascar'|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/dreamworks-animation-takes-57m-write-777474|accessdate=November 4, 2015|work=The Hollywood Reporter|date=February 24, 2015}}</ref><ref name=PRN4Q2014>{{cite press release|author1=DreamWorks Animation SKG|title=DreamWorks Animation Reports Fourth Quarter And Year-End 2014 Financial Results|url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/dreamworks-animation-reports-fourth-quarter-and-year-end-2014-financial-results-300040670.html|publisher=PR Newswire|accessdate=November 4, 2015|date=February 24, 2015}}</ref>\n\n''Penguins of Madagascar'' was released on November 26, 2014 in North America and Canada across 3,764 theatres. It earned $6.25 million on its opening day and $3.95 million the next day on [[Thanksgiving (United States)|Thanksgiving Day]].<ref>{{cite magazine | url = https://deadline.com/2014/11/mockingjay-penguins-of-madagascar-horrible-bosses-2-thanksgiving-box-office-1201299198/ | title = \u2018Mockingjay\u2019, \u2018Penguins\u2019 & \u2018Horrible Bosses 2\u2032 Cook Up T-Giving Box Office | author = Nancy Tartaglione | magazine = Deadline.com | date = November 27, 2014 | accessdate = November 28, 2014}}</ref> It earned $10.5 million [[Black Friday (shopping)|on Black Friday]].<ref>{{cite magazine | url = https://variety.com/2014/film/news/box-office-mockingjay-rules-black-friday-with-24-1-million-as-horrible-bosses-2-stumbles-1201366810/ | title = Box Office: \u2018Mockingjay\u2019 Rules Black Friday With $24.1 Million as \u2018Horrible Bosses 2\u2019 Stumbles | author = Maane Khatchatourian | magazine = Variety | date = November 19, 2014 | accessdate = November 30, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine | url = https://deadline.com/2014/11/hunger-games-box-office-thanksgiving-penguins-of-madgascar-horrible-bosses-2-1201301187/ | title = \u2018Mockingjay\u2019 Flies Away With Black Friday Cash; \u2018Penguins\u2019, \u2018Bosses\u2019 Left With Bones | author = Anthony D'Alessandro | magazine = Deadline.com | date = November 29, 2014 | accessdate = November 30, 2014}}</ref> The film underperformed during its opening weekend earning $25.4 million and debuting at #2 at the box office behind ''[[The Hunger Games: Mockingjay \u2013 Part 1]]'', for which 3D accounted for 24% of its opening-weekend gross.<ref>{{cite magazine | url = https://deadline.com/2014/11/hunger-games-box-office-thanksgiving-penguins-of-madgascar-horrible-bosses-2-1201301187/ | title = \u2018Mockingjay,\u2019 Holdovers Strong As Turkey Turnstiles Slow: Box Office | author = Anthony D'Alessandro | magazine = Deadline.com | date = November 30, 2014 |access-date= December 1, 2014}}</ref> The opening-weekend audience was evenly split among those under and over the age of 25, with 58% and female accounted 51%. In [[CinemaScore]] polls conducted during the opening weekend, cinema audiences gave ''Penguins of Madagascar'' an average grade of A- on an A+ to F scale.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.boxofficemojo.com/news/?id=3968&p=.htm | title = Weekend Report: \u2018Hunger Games\u2019 Devours Undercooked Franchise Titles Over Thanksgiving | author = Ray Subers | website = Box Office Mojo | date = November 30, 2014 | accessdate = December 29, 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe film was released in [[China]] on November 14,<ref name=DeadlineHitChina /> two weeks ahead of its North American debut, and earned $11.3 million from 3,500 screens, debuting at number two at the Chinese box office behind ''[[Interstellar (film)|Interstellar]]'' ($42 million).<ref>{{cite magazine | url = https://deadline.com/2014/11/international-box-office-interstellar-penguins-of-madagascar-china-dumb-and-dumber-to-big-hero-6-1201286020/ | title = \u2018Interstellar\u2019 Blasts Past $200M With $42M China Lift-Off: International Box Office | author = Nancy Tartaglione | magazine = Deadline.com | date = November 16, 2014 | accessdate = November 17, 2014}}</ref> In its opening weekend, the film earned $36.5 million from 47 markets.<ref name=\"1stweek\">{{cite web | url = https://www.boxofficemojo.com/news/?id=3969&p=.htm | title = Around-the-World Roundup: 'Mockingjay' Repeats, 'Interstellar' Nears $400 Million | author = Ray Subers | website = Box Office Mojo | date = November 30, 2014 | accessdate = December 19, 2014}}</ref> Overall, the top openings were in Russia ($8.2 million), Korea ($6 million), Italy ($4.63 million), Germany ($4.2 million), and Australia ($3.68 million).<ref name=\"Update\">{{cite web | url = https://deadline.com/2014/11/international-box-office-hunger-games-mockingjay-penguins-madagascar-paddington-horrible-bosses-interstellar-weekend-results-1201302872/ | title = \u2018Mockingjay\u2019, \u2018Interstellar\u2019, \u2018Penguins\u2019 Lead Frame; \u2018Paddington\u2019 Charms UK: Int\u2019l B.O. Update | author = Nancy Tartaglione | date = November 30, 2014 | accessdate = December 1, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"$500million\">{{cite magazine | url = https://deadline.com/2015/01/international-box-office-hobbit-taken-3-american-sniper-pk-angel-of-death-1201340651/ | title = \u2018Hobbit\u2019 Passes $500M; \u2018American Sniper\u2019, \u2018Taken 3\u2032 Skillful: Intl Box Office Update | author = Nancy Tartaglione | magazine = Deadline.com | date = January 4, 2015 | accessdate = January 5, 2015}}</ref> The film's opening in Germany was the second-highest for an animated film in 2014, behind ''[[How to Train Your Dragon 2]]''.<ref name=\"Update\"/>\n\n===Critical response===\nThe film has a 73% rating on [[Rotten Tomatoes]] based on 110 reviews, with an average rating of 6.2/10. The site's consensus was \"''Penguins of Madagascar'' is fast and brightly colored enough to entertain small children, but too frantically silly to offer real filmgoing fun for the whole family.\"<ref>{{cite web | url= https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/penguins_of_madagascar/ | title=Penguins of Madagascar | work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] | publisher=[[Fandango Media]] | access-date= January 19, 2019 }}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the film achieved a score of 53 out of 100 based on reviews from 31 critics, indicating \"mixed or average reviews\".<ref>{{cite web | url= https://www.metacritic.com/movie/penguins-of-madagascar | title=Penguins of Madagascar Reviews | work=[[Metacritic]] | publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] | access-date=July 11, 2015}}</ref> Audiences surveyed by [[CinemaScore]] gave the film a grade A\u2013.<ref>https://www.cinemascore.com/publicsearch/index/title/ </ref>\n\nMichael Rechtshaffen of ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' gave the film a negative review, saying \"While there are plenty of madcap antics to fill a feature, all that manic energy ultimately proves to be more exhausting than exhilarating.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/penguins-madagascar-film-review-748219|title='Penguins of Madagascar': Film Review|author=Michael Rechtshaffen|work=The Hollywood Reporter|accessdate=November 26, 2014}}</ref> Elizabeth Weitzman of the ''[[New York Daily News]]'' gave the film three out of five stars, saying \"Granted, it's no classic, but a sassy script and good-natured voice work from Benedict Cumberbatch and John Malkovich should keep kids and grownups entertained over the holidays.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/movies/penguins-madagascar-movie-review-article-1.2022223|title=\u2018Penguins of Madagascar,\u2019 movie review|work=NY Daily News|accessdate=November 26, 2014}}</ref> Ignatiy Vishnevetsky of ''[[The A.V. Club]]'' gave the film a B, saying \"Frenetic and frequently funny, ''Penguins Of Madagascar'' represents the DreamWorks Animation franchise style\u2014which boils down to self-aware, but na\u00efve, talking animals who learn kid-friendly life lessons\u2014at its most palatable.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.avclub.com/review/penguins-madagascar-dreamworks-animation-its-most--212233|title=Review: Penguins Of Madagascar is DreamWorks Animation at its most amusingly energetic |newspaper=[[The A.V. Club]]|accessdate=November 26, 2014}}</ref> Ben Kenigsberg of ''[[The New York Times]]'' gave the film a positive review, saying \"The lack of originality is offset by sheer silliness, including Classified and Skipper's Abbott and Costello-style argument over whether there's a long I in 'diversion.' The word fits the movie.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/11/26/movies/penguins-of-madagascar-with-voice-of-benedict-cumberbatch.html?partner=rss&emc=rss|title=\u2018Penguins of Madagascar,\u2019 With Voice of Benedict Cumberbatch|author=Ben Kenigsberg|work=The New York Times|accessdate=November 26, 2014}}</ref>\n\nBill Zwecker of the ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'' gave the film three out of four stars, saying \"Once again the ''Madagascar'' team have come up with a winner&nbsp;\u2013 a nice way to kick off the Thanksgiving and holiday filmgoing experience for the whole family.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://entertainment.suntimes.com/movies/penguins-madagascar-happy-feat-action-comedy/|title=\u2018Penguins of Madagascar': A happy feat of action, comedy|work=Chicago Sun-Times|accessdate=November 26, 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141208042813/http://entertainment.suntimes.com/movies/penguins-madagascar-happy-feat-action-comedy/|archivedate=December 8, 2014|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Lou Lumenick of the ''[[New York Post]]'' gave the film one out of four stars, saying ''\"Penguins of Madagascar'' is a lazy, noisy ADHD-addled collection of animated clich\u00e9s guaranteed to give anyone older than 5 a headache, even if you don't see it in optional 3-D.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2014/11/25/penguins-of-madagascar-stinks-on-and-off-ice/|title=\u2018Penguins of Madagascar\u2019 stinks on (and off) ice |work=New York Post|accessdate=November 26, 2014}}</ref> Jeff Labrecque of ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' gave the film a C-, saying \"''Penguins of Madagascar'' aims primarily for the kiddies, racing from one frenetic action sequence to another like some haywire Walter Lantz cartoon.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,20876861,00.html|title=Penguins of Madagascar Review - Movie Reviews and News - EW.com|work=EW.com|accessdate=November 26, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Awards and nominations===\n{| class=wikitable style=text-align:center\n|-\n! colspan=4 style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | List of awards and nominations\n|-\n! style=\"background:#ccc|Award/Film Festival\n! style=\"background:#ccc|Category\n! style=\"background:#ccc|Recipient(s)\n! style=\"background:#ccc|Result\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\"|[[42nd Annie Awards]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2014/12/annie-awards-nominations-big-hero-six-lego-movie-full-list-1201304339/|title=Annie Awards Nominations Unveiled|website=Deadline|date=December 1, 2014|first=Patrick|last=Hipes|accessdate=June 22, 2015}}</ref>\n| Outstanding Achievement for Animated Effects in an Animated Production\n| Mitul Patel, Nicolas Delbecq, Santosh Khedkar and Yash Argawal\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Outstanding Achievement for Character Animation in an Animated Feature Production\n| Ravi Kamble\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| Outstanding Achievement for Character Design in an Animated Feature Production\n| Craig Kellman, Joe Moshier, Stevie Lewis and Todd Kurosawa\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n|[[Cinema Audio Society Awards|51st Cinema Audio Society Awards]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2015/01/cas-awards-nominations-2015-guardians-of-the-galaxy-nominees-1201348559/|title=CAS Awards Nominees Sound Familiar \u2013 But Not All Of Them|date=January 13, 2015|website=Deadline|accessdate=June 22, 2015}}</ref>\n|Outstanding Achievement in Sound Mixing for Motion Picture - Animated\n|Tighe Sheldon, Paul N.J. Ottosson, Dennis Sands and Randy K. Singer\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|[[2015 Kids' Choice Awards|28th Kids' Choice Awards]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ibtimes.com/kids-choice-awards-nominees-2015-nominations-refresher-list-march-28-award-show-1861866|title=Kids\u2019 Choice Awards Nominees 2015: A Nominations Refresher List Before The March 28 Award Show|date=March 27, 2015|work=[[International Business Times]]|accessdate=March 29, 2015}}</ref>\n|Favorite Animated Movie\n|rowspan=2|[[Eric Darnell]] and [[Simon J. Smith]]\n|{{Nom}}\n|-\n|[[St. Louis Gateway Film Critics Association|11th St. Louis Film Critics Association Awards]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.awardsdaily.com/blog/2014/12/st-louis-film-critic-nominees/|title=St Louis Film Critic Nominees|first=Ryan|last=Adams|date=December 11, 2014|website=Awards Daily|accessdate=June 22, 2015}}</ref>\n|[[St. Louis Gateway Film Critics Association Award for Best Animated Film|Best Animated Film]]\n|{{nom}}\n|}\n\n==Soundtrack==\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Penguins of Madagascar: Music from the Motion Picture\n| type       = film\n| artist     = [[Lorne Balfe]]\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| released   = {{Start date|2014|11|25}}\n| recorded   = 2014\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Film score]]\n| length     = 52:46\n| label      = [[Relativity Music Group]]\n| producer   = [[Hans Zimmer]]\n| chronology = [[DreamWorks Animation]]\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title =\n| next_year  =\n| misc       = {{Extra chronology\n | artist     = [[DreamWorks Animation]]\n | type       = film\n | prev_title = [[How to Train Your Dragon 2]]\n | prev_year  = 2014\n | title      = Penguins of Madagascar\n | year       = 2014\n | next_title =\n | next_year  =\n}}\n}}\n[[Lorne Balfe]] composed the original score for the film,<ref name=FMRSoundtrack /> making it his first solo debut in a DreamWorks Animation film. Balfe wrote the additional music for the previous two ''[[Madagascar (franchise)|Madagascar]]'' films and helped ''Madagascar'' composer [[Hans Zimmer]] with the score for ''[[Megamind]]''. The soundtrack was released on November 25, 2014, by [[Relativity Media|Relativity Music Group]].<ref name=FMRSoundtrack>{{cite web|title=\u2018Penguins of Madagascar\u2019 Soundtrack Announced|url=http://filmmusicreporter.com/2014/11/13/penguins-of-madagascar-soundtrack-announced/|publisher=Film Music Reporter|accessdate=November 15, 2014|date=November 13, 2014}}</ref> Relativity also released an [[Extended play|EP]], ''Penguins of Madagascar: Black & White Christmas Album'', which featured five holiday songs.<ref name=FMRSoundtrack />\n\n{{Track listing\n| total_length = \n| title1       = The Penguins of Madagascar\n| length1      = 4:10 \n| title2       = Antarctica\n| length2      = 3:31 \n| title3       = Demersus\n| length3      = 2:53 \n| title4       = Sclateri\n| length4      = 3:25 \n| title5       = Adeliae\n| length5      = 3:31 \n| title6       = Forsteri\n| length6      = 2:52 \n| title7       = Patagonicus\n| length7      = 3:03\n| title8       = Magellanicus\n| length8      = 1:24 \n| title9       = Private\u2019s Theme\n| length9      = 2:34 \n| title10      = Robustus\n| length10     = 3:36 \n| title11      = Eudyptula Minor\n| length11     = 1:35 \n| title12      = Chrysolophus\n| length12     = 2:51 \n| title13      = Chrysocome\n| length13     = 1:59 \t\n| title14      = Antipodes\n| length14     = 1:20 \n| title15      = Schlegeli\n| length15     = 2:46 \t\n| title16      = Mendiculus\n| length16     = 3:14 \n| title17      = Papua\n| length17     = 1:56 \n| title18      = Humboldti\n| length18     = 2:52 \n| title19      = He Is Dave\n| note19       = featuring [[Antony Genn]]\n| length19     = 3:14 \n}}\n\n==Video game==\nA video game based on the film, titled ''Penguins of Madagascar'', and published by Little Orbit, was released on November 25, 2014 for [[Nintendo 3DS]], [[Wii]], and [[Wii U]].<ref>{{cite press release|title=Smile and Wave, Boys! Little Orbit Announces Penguins of Madagascar Video Game|url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/smile-and-wave-boys-little-orbit-announces-penguins-of-madagascar-video-game-274336461.html|publisher=PR Newswire|accessdate=September 11, 2014|date=September 8, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* {{Official website|http://madagascar.dreamworks.com/movies/penguins-of-madagascar}}\n* {{IMDb title|1911658}}\n* {{mojo title|penguinsofmadagascar}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes|the_penguins_of_madagascar}}\n* {{metacritic film|penguins-of-madagascar}}\n\n{{Madagascar (franchise)}}\n{{DreamWorks Animation}}\n{{Eric Darnell}}\n{{Simon J. Smith}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Penguins Of Madagascar, The (film)}}\n[[Category:2014 films]]\n[[Category:2014 3D films]]\n[[Category:3D animated films]]\n[[Category:2014 computer-animated films]]\n[[Category:2010s action films]]\n[[Category:2010s adventure films]]\n[[Category:2010s American animated films]]\n[[Category:2010s children's comedy films]]\n[[Category:20th Century Fox animated films]]\n[[Category:20th Century Fox films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:Madagascar (franchise) films]]\n[[Category:American 3D films]]\n[[Category:American action comedy films]]\n[[Category:American children's animated comedy films]]\n[[Category:American computer-animated films]]\n[[Category:Animated action films]]\n[[Category:Animated films about penguins]]\n[[Category:Animated films about wolves]]\n[[Category:DreamWorks Animation animated films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Film spin-offs]]\n[[Category:Films about polar bears]]\n[[Category:Films featuring anthropomorphic characters]]\n[[Category:Films set in Shanghai]]\n[[Category:Films set in New York City]]\n[[Category:Films set in Venice]]\n[[Category:Films set in zoos]]\n[[Category:IMAX films]]\n[[Category:2010s spy comedy films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Eric Darnell]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Simon J. Smith]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Lorne Balfe]]\n[[Category:2010s action comedy films]]\n", "name_user": "Greenboy210", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Penguins_of_Madagascar"}
{"title_page": "Isle of Man", "text_new": "{{short description |Island in the Irish Sea}}\n{{For| the racehorse|Isle of Man (horse)}}\n{{pp-move |small= yes}}\n{{coord|54|14|06|N|04|31|30|W|display=title}}\n{{Use British English|date= July 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date= February 2019}}\n{{Infobox dependency\n| name = Isle of Man\n| native_name = {{nobold|{{native name|gv|Mannin, Ellan Vannin}}}}\n| settlement_type = [[Crown dependencies|Crown dependency]]\n| linking_name = the Isle of Man\n| image_flag = Flag of the Isle of Mann.svg\n| flag_size = 130px\n| flag_link = Flag of the Isle of Man\n| image_seal = Coat of arms of the Isle of Man.svg\n| seal_size = 81px\n| seal_type = Coat of arms\n| seal_link = Coat of arms of the Isle of Man\n| motto = {{native phrase|la|\"Quocunque Jeceris Stabit\"|italics=off}}<br>({{lang-en|\"Wherever you throw it, it shall stand\"}})\n| anthem = \"[[O Land of Our Birth]]\"<br />\"[[God Save the Queen]]\" <div style=\"display:inline-block;margin-top:0.4em;\">[[File:United States Navy Band - God Save the Queen.ogg]]</div>\n| image_map = Europe-Isle_of_Man.svg\n| mapsize = 290px\n| map_alt = Location of the Isle of Man in Europe\n| map_caption = Location of the Isle of Man (green) in Europe (dark grey)\n| subdivision_type = [[Sovereign state]]\n| subdivision_name = [[United Kingdom]]\n| established_title = [[Kingdom of the Isles|Norse control]]\n| established_date = 9th century\n| established_title2 = [[Treaty of Perth|Scottish control]]\n| established_date2 = 2 July 1266\n| established_title3 = English control\n| established_date3 = 1399\n| established_title4 = [[Isle of Man Purchase Act 1765|Revested into British Crown]]\n| established_date4 = 10 May 1765\n| official_languages = [[English language|English]] <br> [[Manx language|Manx]]\n| capital = [[Douglas, Isle of Man|Douglas]]\n| coordinates = {{Coord|54|09|N|4|29|W|type:city}}\n| largest_city = capital\n| demonym = [[Manx people|Manx]] (Manxman (plural: Manxmen), Manxwoman (plural: Manxwomen))\n| ethnic_groups =\n| ethnic_groups_year =\n| religion = Largely Christian\n| government_type = [[Parliamentary system|Parliamentary]] [[Democracy|democratic]] [[constitutional monarchy]]\n| leader_title1 = [[Lord of Mann]]<!---Please do not change this to \"Lady\", the title is \"Lord\"--->\n| leader_name1 = [[Elizabeth II]]\n| leader_title2 = [[Lieutenant Governor of the Isle of Man|Lieutenant&nbsp;governor]]\n| leader_name2 = [[Richard Gozney|Sir Richard Gozney]]\n| leader_title3 = [[Chief Minister of the Isle of Man|Chief Minister]]\n| leader_name3 = [[Howard Quayle]]\n| legislature = [[Tynwald]]\n| upper_house = [[Legislative Council of the Isle of Man|Legislative Council]]\n| lower_house = [[House of Keys]]\n| area_km2 = 572\n| area_rank = {{small|unranked}} <!-- Area rank should match [[List of countries and dependencies by area]];(should not be any here as it is listed with a dash) -->\n| area_sq_mi = 221<!-- Do not remove per [[WP:MOSNUM]] -->\n| percent_water = 1\n| elevation_max_m = 620\n| population_census = 83,314<ref name=\"census-2016\">{{cite web |url= https://www.gov.im/media/1355784/2016-isle-of-man-census-report.pdf |title= 2016 Isle of Man Census Report |website= Gov.im |accessdate= 19 July 2019}}</ref>\n| population_estimate_rank = 202nd\n| population_census_year = 2016\n| population_density_km2 = 148\n| population_density_sq_mi = 362.4<!-- Do not remove per [[WP:MOSNUM]] -->\n| population_density_rank = 78th\n| GDP_PPP = $7.43&nbsp;billion\n| GDP_PPP_year = 2014\n| GDP_PPP_rank = 161st\n| GDP_PPP_per_capita = $84,600\n| GDP_PPP_per_capita_rank = 9th\n| Gini = 0.41 <!--number only-->\n| Gini_year =\n| Gini_change = <!--increase/decrease/steady-->\n| Gini_ref = <ref>{{cite web | url= http://www.poverty.org.uk/09/index.shtml | title= Income Inequalities | work= The Poverty Site | access-date= 21 April 2011 | archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20110426071007/http://www.poverty.org.uk/09/index.shtml | archive-date= 26 April 2011 |url-status= dead }}</ref>\n| HDI = 0.849 <!--number only-->\n| HDI_year = 2010\n| HDI_change = <!--increase/decrease/steady-->\n| HDI_ref = <ref>{{cite web |url= http://hdr.undp.org/en/media/HDR_2010_EN_Table1.pdf | title= Human Development Report 2010 | work= HDR.UNDP.org | publisher= United Nations Development Programme | access-date= 21 April 2011 | page= 143 ff}}</ref>\n| HDI_rank = 14th\n| currency = [[Pound sterling]]<br />[[Manx pound]] (\u00a3)\n| currency_code = GBP\n| timezone = [[Greenwich Mean Time|GMT]]\n| utc_offset = \u00b100:00\n| timezone_DST = [[British Summer Time|BST]]\n| utc_offset_DST = +01:00\n| date_format = dd/mm/yyyy\n| electricity = 240 V\u201350 Hz\n| drives_on = left\n| calling_code = [[Telephone numbers in the United Kingdom#Isle of Man|+44]]\n| postal_code_type = [[Postcodes in the United Kingdom#Crown dependencies|UK postcode]]\n| postal_code = [[IM postcode area|IM1 \u2013 IM99]]\n| iso_code = [[ISO 3166-2:IM|IM]]\n| cctld = [[.im]]\n}}\nThe '''Isle of Man''' ({{lang-gv|Mannin}} {{IPA-gv|\u02c8man\u026an\u02b2|}}, also {{lang-gv|Ellan Vannin}} {{IPA-gv|\u02c8\u025bl\u02b2an \u02c8van\u026an\u02b2|}}), also known as '''Mann''' {{IPAc-en|m|\u00e6|n}}, is a self-governing British [[Crown dependencies|Crown dependency]] situated in the [[Irish Sea]] between [[Great Britain]] and [[Ireland]]. The [[head of state]], [[Queen Elizabeth II]], holds the title of [[Lord of Mann]] and is represented by a [[Lieutenant Governor of the Isle of Man|lieutenant governor]]. The [[United Kingdom]] has responsibility for the island's defence.\n\nHumans have lived on the island since before 6500 BC. [[Gaels|Gaelic]] cultural influence began in the 5th century AD, and the [[Manx language]], a branch of the [[Goidelic languages]], emerged. In 627 King [[Edwin of Northumbria]] conquered the Isle of Man along with most of [[Mercia]]. In the 9th century [[Norsemen]] established the [[thalassocratic]] [[Kingdom of the Isles]], which included the Isle of Man. [[Magnus Barefoot|Magnus III]], King of Norway from 1093 to 1103, reigned also as [[King of Mann and the Isles]] between 1099 and 1103.<ref>{{cite web | title = Magnus 3 Olavsson Berrf\u00f8tt \u2013 Norsk biografisk leksikon | website = Store norske leksikon | url = https://nbl.snl.no/Magnus_3_Olavsson_Berrf%C3%B8tt | language = no | access-date = 2019-08-15 | date= 28 September 2014 }}</ref>\n\nIn 1266 the island became part of [[Kingdom of Scotland|Scotland]] under the [[Treaty of Perth]], after being ruled by [[Norway]]. After a period of alternating rule by the kings of Scotland and [[Kingdom of England|England]], the island came under the feudal lordship of the [[The Crown|English Crown]] in 1399. The lordship [[Isle of Man Purchase Act 1765|revested]] into the British Crown in 1765, but the island never became part of the 18th-century [[kingdom of Great Britain]], nor of its successors, the [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland]] and the present-day United Kingdom. It has always retained its internal self-government.\n\nIn 1881 the Isle of Man [[parliament]], [[Tynwald]], became the first national [[legislative body]] in the world to give [[Women's suffrage|women the right to vote]] in a general election, although this excluded married women.<ref>{{Cite web | url= http://www.tynwald.org.im/education/women/Pages/VotesForWomen.aspx | title= Tynwald, the parliament of the Isle of Man: Adult suffrage | date= 2017 | website= Tynwald.org.im | access-date= 2 December 2017}}</ref><ref>In 1893 New Zealand became the first country to grant ''all'' women the vote.</ref> In 2016 [[UNESCO]] awarded the Isle of Man [[World Network of Biosphere Reserves|biosphere reserve status]].<ref>{{Cite web |url= http://www.unesco.org/new/en/natural-sciences/environment/ecological-sciences/biosphere-reserves/europe-north-america/united-kingdom-of-great-britain-and-northern-ireland/isle-of-man/ |title= UNESCO: Isle of Man biosphere reserve |date= | access-date= 2 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nInsurance and [[online gambling]] each generate 17% of the [[gross national product|GNP]], followed by [[information and communications technology]] and banking with 9% each.<ref>{{Cite web |url= https://www.gov.im/media/1359185/national-income-2015-16-report-final.pdf |title= Isle of Man: National Income Report |last= | first= | date= | website= gov.im |access-date= 3 December 2017}}</ref> Internationally, the Isle of Man is known for the [[Isle of Man TT]] (Tourist Trophy) motorcycle races<ref>{{Cite news |url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/travel/destinations/europe/united-kingdom/england/isle-of-man/articles/great-british-drivesisleofman/ |title= Great British drives: Isle of Man |last= Williams |first= David |date= 2017-10-03 |work= The Telegraph |access-date= 2019-08-15 |language= en-GB |issn= 0307-1235 | quote = The Isle of Man is best known, of course, for its famous race, the annual Tourist Trophy, or 'TT'. }}\n</ref> and for the [[Manx cat]], a breed of cat with short or no tails.<ref>\n{{cite book\n | last1 = Long\n | first1 = Peter\n | year = 1998\n | chapter = Isle of Man\n | title = The Hidden Places of England\n | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=4ePshlzYVkAC\n | series = Hidden Places - National Guides\n | edition = 4\n | location = Aldermaston\n | publisher = Travel Publishing Ltd\n | publication-date = 2004\n | page = 281\n | isbn = 9781904434122\n | access-date = 9 March 2020\n | quote = Best known for its motorcycle races, its tailless cats and its kippers [...].\n}}\n</ref>\nThe inhabitants ([[Manx people|Manx]]) are considered a [[Celtic Nations|Celtic nation]].<ref>\n{{Cite book\n|url= https://books.google.com/?id=NwvoM-ZFoAgC\n|title= One Europe, Many Nations: A Historical Dictionary of European National Groups\n|first= James|last= Minahan|date= 31 January 2000\n|publisher= Greenwood Publishing Group|isbn= 9780313309847\n|via= Google Books\n}}</ref>\n\n== Name ==\nThe Manx name of the Isle of Man is ''{{lang|gv|Ellan Vannin}}'': ''{{lang|gv|ellan}}'' ({{IPA-gv|\u025bl\u02b2an}}) is a Manx word meaning \"island\"; ''{{lang|gv|Mannin}}'' ({{IPA-gv|man\u026an\u02b2|IPA}}) appears in the [[genitive case]] as ''{{lang|gv|Vannin}}'' ({{IPA-gv|van\u026an\u02b2|IPA}}), with [[Consonant mutation#Celtic languages|initial consonant mutation]], hence ''{{lang|gv|Ellan Vannin}}'', \"Island of Mann\". The short form used in English is spelled either Mann or Man. The earliest recorded Manx form of the name is ''{{lang|gv|Manu}}'' or ''{{lang|gv|Mana}}''.<ref>{{Cite book | last=Kinvig | first=R. H. | title=The Isle of Man: A Social, Cultural and Political History | page=18 |date=1975 | edition=3rd | isbn=0-85323-391-8 | publisher=Liverpool University Press | ref=harv }}</ref>\n\nThe [[Old Irish]] form of the name is ''{{lang|sga|Manau}}'' or ''{{lang|sga|Mano}}''. [[Old Welsh]] records named it as ''{{lang|owl|Manaw}}'', also reflected in ''{{lang|owl|[[Manaw Gododdin]]}}'', the name for an ancient district in north Britain along the lower [[Firth of Forth]].<ref name=\"Koch2006\">\n{{Cite book\n| last=Koch\n| first=John T.\n| date=2006\n| page=676\n| title=Celtic Culture: A Historical Encyclopedia\n| publisher=ABC-CLIO\n| isbn=978-1-85109-440-0\n| ref=harv\n}}</ref>\nThe oldest known reference to the island calls it ''{{lang|la|Mona}}'', in [[Latin]] ([[Julius Caesar]], 54&nbsp;BC); in the 1st century AD, [[Pliny the Elder]] records it as ''{{lang|la|Monapia}}'' or ''{{lang|la|Monabia}}'', and [[Ptolemy]] (2nd century) as ''Mon\u0153da'' ({{lang|grc|M\u03bf\u03bd\u03b1\u03bf\u03b9\u03b4\u03b1}}, ''Monaoida'') or {{lang|grc|M\u03bf\u03bd\u03b1\u03c1\u03b9\u03bd\u03b1}} (''Monarina''), in [[Koine Greek]].\nLater Latin references have ''{{lang|la|Mevania}}'' or ''{{lang|la|M\u00e6navia}}'' ([[Orosius]], 416),<ref>\n{{Cite journal\n| last1=Rivet\n| first1=A. L. F.\n| last2=Smith\n| first2=Colin\n| date=1979\n| pages=410\u2013411\n| title=The Place Names of Roman Britain\n| publisher=Batsford\n| ref=harv\n}}</ref>\nand ''{{lang|la|Eubonia}}'' or ''{{lang|la|Eumonia}}'' by Irish writers. It is found in the [[Sagas of Icelanders]] as ''{{lang|is|M\u00f6n}}''.<ref>\n{{Harvcolnb|Moore|1903|p=84}}\n{{Harvcolnb|Sacheverell|1859|pp=119\u2013120}}\n{{Harvcolnb|Waldron|1726|p=1}}\n{{Cite book\n| last=Kinvig\n| first=R. H.\n| title=The Isle of Man. A Social, Cultural and Political History.\n| pages=18\u201319\n| date=1975\n| edition=3rd\n| publisher=Liverpool University Press\n| isbn=0-85323-391-8\n| ref=harv\n}}</ref>\n\nThe name is probably cognate with the [[Welsh language|Welsh]] name of the island of [[Anglesey]], ''{{lang|cy|Ynys M\u00f4n}}'',<ref name=\"Koch2006\"/>\nusually derived from a [[Insular Celtic languages|Celtic]] word for 'mountain' (reflected in Welsh ''{{lang|cy|mynydd}}'', [[Breton language|Breton]] ''{{lang|br|menez}}'', and [[Scottish Gaelic]] ''{{lang|gd|monadh}}''),<ref>''[[Indogermanisches Etymologisches W\u00f6rterbuch]]'': Record number 1277 (Root / lemma: men-1)</ref><ref>{{Cite book\n| last=Koch\n| first=John T.\n| title=Celtic Culture: A Historical Encyclopedia\n| publisher=ABC-CLIO\n| page=679\n| isbn=978-1-85109-440-0\n| date=2006\n| ref=harv\n}}</ref>\nfrom a [[Proto-Celtic]] ''*moniyos''.\n\nThe name was at least secondarily associated with that of [[Manann\u00e1n mac Lir]] in [[Irish mythology]] (corresponding to Welsh ''{{lang|owl|[[Manawydan]] fab Ll\u0177r}}'').<ref>{{Cite book | last=Kneale | first=Victor | chapter=Ellan Vannin (Isle of Man). Britonia | editor-last=Koch | editor-first=John T. | title=Celtic Culture: A Historical Encyclopedia | page=676 | date=2006 | place=Santa Barbara | publisher=ABC-CLIO | ref=harv  }} The Old Irish name ''{{lang|sga|Manand\u00e1n}}'' is often interpreted as 'He of [the isle of] Mann'. If the name of Mann reflects the generic word for 'mountain', it is impossible to distinguish this from a generic 'he of the mountain'; but the patronymic ''{{lang|sga|mac Lir}}'', interpreted as 'son of the Sea', is taken to reinforce the association with the island. See, e.g.: Wagner, Heinrich. \"Origins of Pagan Irish Religion\". ''Zeitschrift f\u00fcr Celtische Philologie''. v. 38. 1-28.</ref> In the earliest Irish mythological texts, Manann\u00e1n is a king of the [[otherworld]], but the 9th-century ''[[Sanas Cormaic]]'' identifies a [[Euhemerism|euhemerised]] Manann\u00e1n as \"a famous merchant who resided in, and gave name to, the Isle of Man\".<ref>Cited after ''Catholic World'' 37 (1883) p. 261.<!--where I found this; I am sure we can attribute it to the ms. text more directly with some extra effort--></ref> Later, a Manann\u00e1n is recorded as the first [[king of Mann]] in a Manx poem (dated 1504).<ref>{{cite book|title=The Dublin Review|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Ih4YAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA83|volume=57|year=1865|publisher=W. Spooner|page=83}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n{{Main|History of the Isle of Man}}\n[[File:The Braaid - Isle of Man - kingsley - 21-APR-09.jpg|thumb|left|[[The Braaid]] in the central Isle of Man, with remnants of a Celtic-Norse [[Roundhouse (dwelling)|roundhouse]] and two [[longhouse]]s, c. AD 650\u2013950]]\n\nThe island was cut off from the surrounding islands around 8000&nbsp;BC as sea levels rose following the end of the ice age. Humans colonised it by travelling by sea some time before [[Mesolithic|6500&nbsp;BC]].<ref name=\"Brad8\">{{Cite book |last=Bradley |first=Richard |title=The prehistory of Britain and Ireland |page=8 |publisher=Cambridge University Press |date=2007 |isbn=978-0-521-84811-4 |ref=harv}}</ref> The first occupants were [[hunter-gatherer]]s and fishermen. Examples of their tools are kept at the Manx Museum.<ref>{{cite web | website=Isle of Man Government Manx National Heritage | title=Hunter Gatherers | date=2012-03-16 | url=http://www.gov.im/mnh/collections/archaeology/mesolithic/ | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120316143121/http://www.gov.im/mnh/collections/archaeology/mesolithic/ | archive-date=2012-03-16 | url-status=unfit | access-date=2019-08-15}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Kingdom of Mann and the Isles-en.svg|thumb|right|The [[Kingdom of the Isles]] about the year 1100]]\nThe [[Neolithic Period]] marked the beginning of farming, and the people began to build [[Megalith|megalithic monuments]], such as Cashtal yn Ard near [[Maughold (parish)|Maughold]], [[Godred Crovan|King Orry]]'s Grave at [[Laxey]], Meayll Circle near [[Cregneash]], and Ballaharra Stones at [[St John's, Isle of Man|St John's]]. There were also the local [[Ronaldsway culture|Ronaldsway]] and Bann cultures.<ref>{{cite web | title=First Farmers | website=Isle of Man Government Manx National Heritage | date=2012-11-08 | url=http://www.gov.im/mnh/collections/archaeology/neolithic/ | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121108050257/http://www.gov.im/mnh/collections/archaeology/neolithic/ | archive-date=2012-11-08 | url-status=unfit | access-date=2019-08-15}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[Bronze Age]], the size of burial mounds decreased. The people put bodies into stone-lined graves with ornamental containers. The Bronze Age burial mounds survived as long-lasting markers around the countryside.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gov.im/mnh/collections/archaeology/bronzeage/|title=Home - Manx National Heritage|website=Manx National Heritage|access-date=10 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe ancient Romans knew of the island and called it ''{{lang|la|Insula Manavia}}.''<ref>{{cite web|last1=Esmonde Cleary |first1=A. |first2=R. |last2=Warner |first3=R. |last3=Talbert |first4=S. |last4=Gillies |first5=T. |last5=Elliott |first6=J. |last6=Becker |title=Manavia Insula|url=http://pleiades.stoa.org/places/89242|website=Pleides|publisher=Pleiades|access-date=26 February 2016 }}</ref> Scholars have not determined whether they conquered the island.\n\nAround the 5th century AD, large-scale migration from Ireland precipitated a process of [[Gaelicisation]], evidenced by [[Ogham]] inscriptions, and the [[Manx language]] developed. It is a [[Goidelic languages|Goidelic language]] closely related to [[Irish language|Irish]] and [[Scottish Gaelic]].<ref>{{cite web | website=Isle of Man Government Manx National Heritage | title=Celtic Farmers | date=2012-03-16 | url=http://www.gov.im/mnh/collections/archaeology/ironage/ | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120316143141/http://www.gov.im/mnh/collections/archaeology/ironage/ | archive-date=2012-03-16 | url-status=unfit | access-date=2019-08-15}}</ref>\n\n[[Vikings]] arrived at the end of the 8th century. They established [[Tynwald]] and introduced many land divisions that still exist. In 1266 [[Magnus VI of Norway|King Magnus VI of Norway]] ceded the islands to Scotland in the Treaty of Perth. But Scotland's rule over Mann did not become firmly established until 1275, when the Manx were defeated in the [[Battle of Ronaldsway]], near [[Castletown, Isle of Man|Castletown]].\n\nIn 1290 King [[Edward I of England]] sent [[Walter de Huntercombe, 1st Baron Huntercombe|Walter de Huntercombe]] to take possession of Mann. It remained in English hands until 1313, when [[Robert the Bruce|Robert Bruce]] took it after besieging [[Castle Rushen]] for five weeks. A confused period followed when Mann was sometimes under English rule and sometimes Scottish, until 1346, when the [[Battle of Neville's Cross]] decided the long struggle between England and Scotland in England's favour.\n\nThe Crown delegated its rule of the island to a series of lords and magnates. [[Tynwald]] passed laws concerning the government of the island in all respects and had control over its finances, but was subject to the approval of the [[Lord of Mann]].\n\nIn 1866, the Isle of Man obtained limited home rule, with partly democratic elections to the [[House of Keys]], but the [[Legislative Council of the Isle of Man|Legislative Council]] was appointed by the Crown. Since then, democratic government has been gradually extended.\n\nThe Isle of Man has designated more than 250 historic sites as [[Registered Buildings of the Isle of Man|registered buildings]].\n\n==Geography==\n{{Main|Geography of the Isle of Man}}\n{{See also|Geology of the Isle of Man|List of islands of the Isle of Man|Biota of the Isle of Man}}\n[[File:Sound IOM.JPG|left|upright=1.05|thumb|The [[Calf of Man]] seen from [[Cregneash]]]]\n[[File:Isle of Man by Sentinel-2.jpg|right|upright=1.25|right|thumb|A satellite image]]\n\nThe Isle of Man is located in the middle of the northern [[Irish Sea]], almost equidistant from [[England]] to the east, [[Northern Ireland]] to the west, and [[Scotland]] (closest) to the north; while [[Wales]] to the south is almost the distance of the [[Republic of Ireland]] to the southwest. It is {{convert|52|km}} long and, at its widest point, {{convert|22|km}} wide. It has an area of around {{convert|572|km2}}.<ref name=\"gov.im\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gov.im/isleofman/geography.xml|title=Geography \u2013 Isle of Man Public Services<!-- Bot generated title -->|website=Gov.im|access-date=10 November 2017|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://archive.today/20120526201738/http://www.gov.im/isleofman/geography.xml|archive-date=26 May 2012}}</ref> Besides the island of Mann itself, the political unit of the Isle of Man includes some nearby small islands: the seasonally inhabited [[Calf of Man]],<ref>{{cite book | title = Bird Observatories of Britain and Ireland | last = Archer | first = Mike | isbn = 978-1-4081-1040-9 | publisher = A&C Black | date = 2010 | edition = 2nd}}</ref> [[Chicken Rock]] on which stands an unmanned lighthouse, [[St Patrick's Isle]] and [[St Michael's Isle]]. The last two of these are connected to the main island by permanent roads/causeways.\n\nRanges of hills in the north and south are separated by a central valley. The northern plain, by contrast, is relatively flat, consisting mainly of deposits from glacial advances from western Scotland during colder times. There are more recently deposited [[shingle beach]]es at the northernmost point, the [[Point of Ayre]]. The island has one mountain higher than {{convert|600|m}}, [[Snaefell]], with a height of {{convert|620|m|ft|0}}.<ref name=\"gov.im\" /> According to an old saying, from the summit one can see six kingdoms: those of Mann, Scotland, England, Ireland, Wales, and [[Heaven]].<ref>\n{{cite web |title=Snaefell Mountain Railway |work=Isle of Man Guide |publisher=Maxima Systems |url= http://www.iomguide.com/mountainrailway.php |access-date=5 June 2008 |quote=From the top on a clear day it is said one can see the six kingdoms. The kingdom of Scotland, England, Wales, Northern Ireland, Mann and Heaven.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Snaefell Mountain Railway |website=VisitIsleOfMan.com |publisher=[[Government of the Isle of Man|Isle of Man Government]] |url=http://www.gov.im/tourism/culture/attractions/snaefell_attract.xml |access-date=5 June 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080505014518/http://www.gov.im/tourism/culture/attractions/snaefell_attract.xml |archive-date=5 May 2008 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> Some versions add a seventh kingdom, that of the sea, or [[Neptune (mythology)|Neptune]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Snaefell Summit  |website=Isle-of-Man.com  |url= http://www.isle-of-man.com/manxnotebook/tourism/pcards/snaefell.htm |access-date=5 June 2008 |quote=It is the answer to the often posed question as to where can one see seven kingdoms at the same time? The seven Kingdoms being the four mentioned by Earl James, the Kingdom of Man, of Earth (in some answers that of Neptune) and of Heaven.}}</ref>\n\n=== Population ===\n{{Further|Manx people}}\n[[File:Isle of Man map-en.svg|right|upright=1.05|230px|frameless]]\n\nAt the 2016 census,<ref name=\"census-2016\" /> the Isle of Man was home to 83,314 people, of whom 26,997 resided in the island's [[capital city|capital]], [[Douglas, Isle of Man|Douglas]], and 9,128 in the adjoining village of [[Onchan]]. The population decreased by 1.4% between the 2011 and 2016 censuses. By country of birth, those born in the Isle of Man were the largest group (49.8%), while those born in the United Kingdom were the next largest group at 40% (33.9% in [[England]], 3% in [[Scotland]], 2% in [[Northern Ireland]] and 1.1% in Wales), 1.8% in the [[Republic of Ireland]] and 0.75% in the [[Channel Islands]]. The remaining 8.5% were born elsewhere in the world, with 5% coming from EU countries (other than the UK and Ireland).\n\n==== Census ====\n<!-- This section is linked from (redirect) [[Census in the Isle of Man]] -->\nThe ''Isle of Man Full Census'', last held in 2016,<ref name=\"census-2016\" /> has been a decennial occurrence since 1821, with interim censuses being introduced from 1966. It is separate from, but similar to, the [[Census in the United Kingdom]].\n\nThe 2001 census was conducted by the Economic Affairs Division of the [[Isle of Man Treasury]], under the authority of the Census Act 1929.\n\n== Government ==\n{{Main|Isle of Man Government}}\nThe United Kingdom is responsible for the island's defence and ultimately for [[good governance]], and for representing the island in international forums, while the island's own parliament and government have competence over all domestic matters.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.isleofmanfinance.gov.im/About/political.xml|title=Isle of Man Government website|website=Isleofmanfinance.gov.im|access-date=10 November 2017|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081014033149/http://www.isleofmanfinance.gov.im/About/political.xml|archive-date=14 October 2008}}</ref>\n\n=== Socio-political structure ===\n{{See also|Manx law}}\nThe island's parliament, [[Tynwald]], is claimed to have been in continuous existence since 979 or earlier, purportedly making it the oldest continuously governing body in the world, though evidence supports a much later date.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bl.uk/onlinegallery/takingliberties/staritems/322chronicleofmann.html|title=Taking Liberties - Star Items - Chronicle of Mann|website=BL.uk|access-date=28 February 2015}}</ref> Tynwald is a [[Tricameralism#Isle of Man|bicameral or tricameral]] legislature, comprising the [[House of Keys]] (directly elected by universal suffrage with a voting age of 16 years) and the [[Legislative Council of the Isle of Man|Legislative Council]] (consisting of indirectly elected and [[Ex officio member|ex-officio members]]). These two bodies also meet together in joint session as Tynwald Court.\n\nThe executive branch of government is the [[Council of Ministers of the Isle of Man|Council of Ministers]], which is composed of members of the House of Keys. It is headed by the [[Chief Minister of the Isle of Man|Chief Minister]], currently (2019) [[Howard Quayle]] [[Member of the House of Keys|MHK]].\n\n[[Vice-regal]] functions of the head of state are performed by a [[Lieutenant Governor of the Isle of Man|lieutenant governor]].\n\n=== External relations and security ===\n{{Main|External relations of the Isle of Man}}\nIn various laws of the United Kingdom, \"the United Kingdom\" is defined to exclude the Isle of Man. Historically, the UK has taken care of its external and defence affairs, and retains paramount power to legislate for the Island. However, in 2007, the Isle of Man and the UK signed an agreement<ref name=\"framework\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gov.im/lib/docs/cso/iominternationalidentityframework.pdf|title=Framework for developing the international identity of the Isle of Man|publisher=|accessdate=14 November 2018}}</ref> that established frameworks for the development of the international identity of the Isle of Man. There is no separate Manx citizenship. Citizenship is covered by UK law, and Manx people are classed as British citizens. The Isle of Man holds neither membership nor associate membership of the European Union, and lies outside the [[European Economic Area]] (EEA). There is a long history of relations and cultural exchange between the Isle of Man and Ireland. The Isle of Man's historic [[Manx language]] (and its modern revived variant) are closely related to both Scottish Gaelic and the Irish language, and in 1947, Irish Taoiseach [[\u00c9amon de Valera]] spearheaded efforts to save the dying Manx language.\n\n==== Defence ====\nUnder [[British law]], the Isle of Man is not part of the United Kingdom. However, the UK takes care of its external and defence affairs.<ref>{{cite report | title = Royal Commission on the Constitution 1969\u20131973, Volume I, Report (Cmnd 5460)|date=1973 | location = London}}</ref> There are no independent military forces on the Isle of Man, although [[HMS Ramsey (M110)|HMS ''Ramsey'']] is affiliated with the [[Ramsey, Isle of Man|town of the same name]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.royalnavy.mod.uk/operations-and-support/surface-fleet/mine-countermeasure/sandown-class/hms-ramsey/ | title = HMS Ramsey | publisher = Royal Navy | date = 2009 | access-date =11 September 2011}}</ref> From 1938 to 1955 there was the [[Manx Regiment]] of the British [[Territorial Army (United Kingdom)|Territorial Army]], which saw extensive action during the [[World War II|Second World War]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.iomguide.com/douglas/regimental-museum.php | title = Regimental Museum \u2013 History | work = Isle of Man Guide | access-date =11 September 2011 }}</ref> In 1779, the [[Manx Fencible Corps]], a [[fencible]] regiment of three companies, was raised; it was disbanded in 1783 at the end of the [[American War of Independence]]. Later, the [[Royal Manx Fencibles]] was raised at the time of the [[French Revolutionary Wars]] and [[Napoleonic Wars]]. The 1st Battalion (of 3 companies) was raised in 1793. A 2nd Battalion (of 10 companies) was raised in 1795,<ref>See {{cite web | title=The Forgotten Army: Fencible Regiments of Great Britain 1793-1816 | website=The Napoleon Series | url=http://www.napoleon-series.org/military/organization/fencibles/c_fencibles2.html | access-date=2019-08-15}} for more detail.</ref> and it saw action during the [[Irish Rebellion of 1798]]. The regiment was disbanded in 1802.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Scobie |first=Ian Hamilton Mackay| date=1914|title=An Old Highland Fencible Corps: The history of the Reay Fencible Highland Regiment of Foot, or Mackay's Highlanders, 1794\u20131802, with an account of its services in Ireland during the rebellion of 1798 |location=Edinburgh |publisher=Blackwood |url=https://archive.org/stream/oldhighlandfenci00scobuoft#page/415/mode/1up |page=363 |ref=harv}}{{inconsistent citations|date=December 2017}}</ref> A third body of Manx Fencibles was raised in 1803 to defend the island during the [[Napoleonic Wars]] and to assist the Revenue. It was disbanded in 1811.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.isle-of-man.com/manxnotebook/history/military/regts.htm|title=Regiments stationed on Isle of Man, 1765-1896|website=Isle-of-man.com|access-date=28 February 2015}}</ref> In 2015 a multi-capability recruiting and training unit of the [[Army Reserve (United Kingdom)|British Army Reserve]] was established in Douglas.<ref name=\"Isle of Man Army Reserve\">{{cite news|title=British Army opens first reserve unit opens on Isle of Man since 1968|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-isle-of-man-34401508|newspaper=BBC News|publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation|access-date=24 October 2016|date=October 2015}}</ref>\n\n====Manxman status====\n{{Main|Manx passport}}\n[[File:Isle of man passport.jpg|thumb|right|''British passport (Isle of Man)'']]\n\nThere is no citizenship of the Isle of Man as such under the British Nationality Acts [[British Nationality Act 1948|1948]] and [[British Nationality Act 1981|1981]].\n\nThe Passport Office, Isle of Man, Douglas, accepts and processes applications for the [[Lieutenant Governor of the Isle of Man]], who is formally responsible for issuing Isle of Man\u2013issued British passports, entitled \"''British Islands \u2013 Isle of Man''{{-\"}}.\n\nBritish citizens who have 'Manxman status', not being either born, naturalised or registered in the United Kingdom, and without a parent or grandparent who has, or if they have not themselves personally been resident in the United Kingdom for more than five consecutive years, do not have the same rights as other British citizens with regard to employment and establishment in other parts of the EU (other than the UK and Ireland).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gov.im/media/624101/protocol3relationshipwiththeeu.pdf|title=Isle of Man Relationship with the European Union|last=|first=|date=|website=www.gov.im|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nIsle of Man-issued British passports can presently be issued to any British citizen resident in the Isle of Man, and also to British citizens who have a qualifying close personal connection to the Isle of Man but are now resident either in the UK or in either one of the two other Crown Dependencies.\n\n==== European Union ====\n{{update|section|Needs updating to reflect Brexit|date=January 2020}}\nThe Isle of Man has never been part of the [[European Union]], nor did it have a [[Special member state territories and the European Union|special status]], and thus it did not take part in the 2016 [[2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum|referendum]] on the UK's [[European Union|EU]] membership. However, Protocol 3 of the UK's Act of Accession to the [[Treaty of Rome]] included the Isle of Man within the [[EU's customs area]], allowing for trade in Manx goods without tariffs throughout the EU.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gov.im/lib/docs/ebusiness/advantages/protocol3.pdf|title=Manx government explanation of Protocol 3|website=Gov.im|access-date=10 November 2017|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080910004526/http://www.gov.im/lib/docs/ebusiness/advantages/protocol3.pdf|archive-date=10 September 2008}}</ref> As it is not part of the [[EU's internal market]], there are still limitations on the movement of capital, services and labour.\n\nEU citizens are entitled to travel and reside, but not work, in the island without restriction. British citizens with Manxman status are under the same circumstances and restrictions as any other non-EU European relating country to work in the EU.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gov.im/categories/business-and-industries/iom-key-facts-guide/island-facts/|title=Isle of Man Facts & Economic Data|work=Isle of Man Finance|publisher=Isle of Man Government|access-date=12 September 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304050532/https://www.gov.im/categories/business-and-industries/iom-key-facts-guide/island-facts/|archivedate=4 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gov.im/lib/docs/cso/immigrationintheisleofmanpub.pdf|title=Immigration in the Isle of Man|publisher=Isle of Man Government|page=12|date=October 2006|access-date=12 September 2010}}</ref>\n\nThe political and diplomatic impacts of [[Brexit]] on the island are still uncertain. The UK has confirmed that the Crown Dependencies' positions were included in the [[Brexit negotiations]].<ref name=\"GRBWP\">{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/604514/Great_repeal_bill_white_paper_print.pdf|title=Legislating for the United Kingdom's withdrawal from the European Union |publisher=Department for Exiting the European Union |date=30 March 2017}}</ref> The [[Brexit withdrawal agreement]] explicitly includes the Isle of Man in its territorial scope, but makes no other mention of it.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ec.europa.eu/commission/sites/beta-political/files/draft_withdrawal_agreement_0.pdf|title=Draft Agreement on the withdrawal of the United Kingdom of Great Britain and Northern Ireland from the European Union|publisher=European Commission|date=14 November 2018}}</ref> The island's government website states that after the end of the implementation period, the Isle of Man's relationship with the EU will depend on the agreement reached between the UK and the EU on their future relationship.<ref>https://www.gov.im/about-the-government/government/brexit/</ref>\n\n==== Commonwealth of Nations ====\nThe Isle of Man is not itself a member of the [[Commonwealth of Nations]]. By virtue of its relationship with the United Kingdom, it takes part in several Commonwealth institutions, including the [[Commonwealth Parliamentary Association]] and the [[Commonwealth Games]]. The [[Government of the Isle of Man]] has made calls for a more integrated relationship with the Commonwealth,<ref>{{cite web|title=The role and future of the Commonwealth|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201213/cmselect/cmfaff/114/11410.htm|publisher=House of Commons|access-date=18 March 2013}}</ref> including more direct representation and enhanced participation in Commonwealth organisations and meetings, including Commonwealth Heads of Government Meetings.<ref>{{cite web|title=Written evidence from the States of Guernsey|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201213/cmselect/cmfaff/114/114we18.htm|publisher=Policy Council of Guernsey|access-date=18 March 2013}}</ref> The [[Chief Minister of the Isle of Man]] has said: \"A closer connection with the Commonwealth itself would be a welcome further development of the island's international relationships.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Isle of Man welcomes report on Commonwealth future |url=http://www.gov.im/lib/news/cso/isleofmanwelcome5.xml |access-date=19 March 2013 |newspaper=Isle of Man Government |date=23 November 2012 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130302143313/http://www.gov.im/lib/news/cso/isleofmanwelcome5.xml |archive-date= 2 March 2013 |df= }}</ref>\n\n== Politics ==\n[[File:IsleOfMan SheadingsAndParishes-en.svg|thumb|right|upright=0.9|Local authorities and [[Local government in the Isle of Man#Sheadings|sheadings]] ]]\n\n{{Main|Politics of the Isle of Man}}\n{{See also|List of political parties in the Isle of Man|Elections in the Isle of Man}}\nMost Manx politicians stand for election as independents rather than as representatives of political parties. Although political parties do exist, their influence is not nearly as strong as in the United Kingdom.\n\nThere are three political parties in the Isle of Man:\n* The [[Liberal Vannin Party]] (established 2006) has two seats in the House of Keys; it promotes greater Manx autonomy and more accountability in government.\n* The [[Manx Labour Party]] is active, and for much of the 20th century had several MHKs, but currently has no seats in either branch of Tynwald.\n* The [[Isle of Man Green Party]] was established in 2016, but currently only has representation at [[Local government in the Isle of Man|local government]] level.<ref>{{cite news |title = Isle of Man Green Party elects first councillor Andrew Bentley |url =https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-isle-of-man-45128963 |work = [[BBC News]]|accessdate=10 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nA number of pressure groups also exist on the island. [[Mec Vannin]] advocate the establishment of a [[sovereignty|sovereign]] [[republic]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mecvannin.im/|title=Mec Vannin|website=Mecvannin.im|access-date=28 February 2015}}</ref> The [[Positive Action Group]] campaign for three key elements to be introduced into the governance of the island: open accountable government, rigorous control of public finances, and a fairer society.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.positiveactiongroup.org/|title=PAG - Positive Action Group - Isle of Man - Positive Action Group - Isle of Man - Pag, Credit, Agreement, User, February|website=Positiveactiongroup.org|access-date=28 February 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Local government ===\n{{Main|Local government in the Isle of Man}}\nLocal government on the Isle of Man is based partly on the island's 17 ancient parishes. There are two types of local authorities:\n* a [[municipal corporation|corporation]] for the Borough of Douglas, and bodies of commissioners for the town districts of [[Castletown, Isle of Man|Castletown]], [[Peel, Isle of Man|Peel]] and [[Ramsey, Isle of Man|Ramsey]], and\n* the village districts of [[Kirk Michael]], [[Onchan]], [[Port Erin]] and [[Port St Mary]], and the 14 \"parish districts\" (those parishes or parts of parishes which do not fall within the districts previously mentioned). Each of these districts also has its own body of commissioners.\n\nLocal authorities are under the supervision of the Isle of Man Government's Department of Local Government and the Environment (DOLGE).\n\n==Public services==\n=== Education ===\n{{Main|Education in the Isle of Man}}\nPublic education is under the Department of Education, Sport & Culture. Thirty-two primary schools, five secondary schools and the [[University College Isle of Man]] function under the department.<ref>{{cite web | title=Department of Education and Children Home Page | website=Isle of Man Government Department of Education and Children | date=2010-11-21 | url=http://www.gov.im/education/ | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101121125241/http://www.gov.im/education/ | archive-date=2010-11-21 | url-status=dead | access-date=2019-08-15}}</ref>\n\n=== Health ===\n{{Main|Health in the Isle of Man}}\nHealth and social care on the Isle of Man is the responsibility of the [[Department of Health and Social Care (Isle of Man)|Department of Health and Social Care]]. Healthcare is free for residents and visitors from the UK.<ref>{{cite web|title=Healthcare on the Isle of Man|url=https://www.locate.im/article/practical-advice/healthcare-on-the-isle-of-man/|website=LOcate IM|access-date=4 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Emergency services ===\nThe Isle of Man Government maintains five emergency services.<ref>{{cite web | title=Emergency services | website=Isle of Man Government | date=2013-08-16 | url=http://cf.gov.im/categories/home-and-neighbourhood/emergency-services/ | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130816235226/http://cf.gov.im/categories/home-and-neighbourhood/emergency-services/ | archive-date=2013-08-16 | url-status=dead | access-date=2019-08-15}}</ref> These are:\n* [[Isle of Man Constabulary]] (police)\n* [[Isle of Man Coastguard]]\n* [[Isle of Man Fire and Rescue Service]]\n* [[Isle of Man Ambulance Service]]\n* [[Isle of Man Civil Defence Corps]]\n\nAll of these services are controlled directly by the [[Department of Home Affairs (Isle of Man)|Department of Home Affairs]] of the Isle of Man Government, and are independent of the United Kingdom. Nonetheless, the Isle of Man Constabulary voluntarily submits to inspection by the British inspectorate of police,<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.gov.im/dha/police/ | title = Welcome to the Isle of Man Constabulary | publisher = Isle of Man Government | access-date = 11 September 2011 | url-status=dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070303101639/http://www.gov.im/dha/police/ | archivedate = 3 March 2007 | df = dmy-all }}</ref> and the Isle of Man Coastguard contracts Her Majesty's Coastguard (UK) for air-sea rescue operations.\n\n===Crematorium===\nThe island's sole crematorium is in Glencrutchery Road, Douglas and is operated by Douglas Borough Council. Usually staffed by four, in March 2020 an increase of staff to 12 was announced by the council leader, responding to the threat of coronavirus which could require more staff.<ref>https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-isle-of-man-51861337</ref>\n\n== Economy ==\n{{Main|Economy of the Isle of Man}}\nThe Isle of Man [[Department for Enterprise (Isle of Man)|Department for Enterprise]] manages the diversified economy in 12 key sectors.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.whereyoucan.com/sectors|title=Isle of Man: Key sectors|date=|access-date=2 December 2017}}</ref> The largest sectors by GNP are insurance and [[Online gambling|eGaming]] with 17% of GNP each, followed by [[Information and communications technology|ICT]] and banking with 9% each. The 2016 census lists 41,636 total employed.<ref name=\"census-2016\" /> The largest sectors by employment are \"medical and health\", \"financial and business services\", construction, retail and public administration.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gov.im/media/1355783/2016-isle-of-man-census-presentation.pdf|title=2016 Isle of Man Census Presentation|date=|access-date=2 December 2017}}</ref> Manufacturing, focused on aerospace and the food and drink industry,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.whereyoucan.com/manufacturing|title=Isle of Man Manufacturing Sector|last=|first=|date=|website=whereyoucan.im (Department for Enterprise)|access-date=2 December 2017}}</ref> employs almost 2000 workers and contributes with about 5% of [[Gross Domestic Product|gross domestic product]] (GDP). The sector provides laser optics, industrial diamonds, electronics, plastics and aerospace precision engineering. Tourism, agriculture, fishing, once the mainstays of the economy, now make very little contributions to the island's GDP.\n\nAfter 30 years of continued GDP growth, the unemployment rate is just around 1%.\n\nThe Isle of Man is a low-tax economy with no [[capital gains tax]], [[wealth tax]], [[stamp duty]], or [[inheritance tax]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gov.im/iomfinance/tax/directtax.xml|title=Financial Services Sector - Isle of Man. Where You Can.|website=Gov.im|publisher=IsleofMan Government|access-date=28 February 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120419122502/http://www.gov.im/iomfinance/tax/directtax.xml|archivedate=19 April 2012}}</ref> and a top rate of [[income tax]] of 20%.<ref name=\"opw\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.im/categories/tax-vat-and-your-money/income-tax-and-national-insurance/individuals/residents/rates-and-allowances/|title=Isle of Man Government: Rates & Allowances 2017/2018|date=2017|website=Gov.im|publisher=Isle of Man Government|access-date=2 December 2017}}</ref> A tax cap is in force: the maximum amount of tax payable by an individual is \u00a3125,000 or \u00a3250,000 for couples if they choose to have their incomes jointly assessed. Personal income is assessed and taxed on a total worldwide income basis rather than a [[remittance]] basis. This means that all income earned throughout the world is assessable for Manx tax rather than only income earned in or brought into the island.\n\nThe standard rate of [[corporate tax|corporation tax]] for residents and non-residents is 0%. Retail business profits above \u00a3500,000 and banking business income are taxed at 10%, and rental (or other) income from land and buildings situated on the Isle of Man is taxed at 20%.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.im/categories/tax-vat-and-your-money/income-tax-and-national-insurance/business-and-corporations/corporate-tax-rates/|title=Isle of Man Government: Corporate Tax Rules|last=|first=|date=|website=Gov.im|access-date=2 December 2017|df=}}</ref>\n[[File:Peel - Peel Bay Beach - geograph.org.uk - 1719663.jpg|thumb|upright=1.15|[[Peel, Isle of Man|Peel]] is the island's main fishing port.]]\n\nTrade takes place mostly with the United Kingdom. The island is in customs union with the UK, and related revenues are pooled and shared under the [[Common Purse Agreement]]. This means that the Isle of Man cannot have the lower excise revenues on alcohol and other goods that are enjoyed in the [[Channel Islands]].\n\nThe Manx government [[Isle of Man Film|promotes island locations for making films]] by offering financial support. Since 1995, over 100 films have been made on the island.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.isleofmanfilm.com/about/|title=Isle of Man Film|date=27 September 2013|access-date=3 December 2017}}</ref> Most recently the island has taken a much wider strategy to attract the general digital media industry in film, television, video and [[eSports]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://isleofmedia.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/Isle-of-Media-National-Strategy.pdf|title=Isle of Man Digital Media Cluster. Strategic Directions for the Isle of Man|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=3 December 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171222064658/http://isleofmedia.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/12/Isle-of-Media-National-Strategy.pdf|archive-date=22 December 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe Isle of Man Government Lottery operated from 1986 to 1997. Since 2 December 1999 the island has participated in the [[National Lottery (United Kingdom)|United Kingdom National Lottery]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ontheisleofman.com/can-i-play-the-national-lottery-on-the-isle-of-man/|title=ontheisleofman.com|website=Ontheisleofman.com|access-date=10 November 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170630005340/http://www.ontheisleofman.com/can-i-play-the-national-lottery-on-the-isle-of-man/|archivedate=30 June 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://lottery.merseyworld.com/Info/Diary.html|title=UK National Lottery Diary|website=Merseyworld.com|access-date=28 February 2015}}</ref> The island is the only jurisdiction outside the United Kingdom where it is possible to play the UK National Lottery.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.national-lottery.co.uk/player/p/help/faqs.ftl#int_GetStarted2|title=National Lottery FAQ:Can I play while overseas?|website=National-lottery.co.uk|access-date=10 November 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140703194651/https://www.national-lottery.co.uk/player/p/help/faqs.ftl#int_GetStarted2|archivedate=3 July 2014}}</ref> Since 2010 it has also been possible for projects in the Isle of Man to receive national lottery [[The National Lottery Awards|Good Causes Funding]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/10361512|title=BBC News - Manx charities to benefit from lottery|newspaper=BBC News|access-date=28 February 2015|date=20 June 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/ld200506/ldselect/ldconst/151/15107.htm|title=House of Lords - Constitution - Ninth Report|website=Parliament.uk|access-date=28 February 2015}}</ref> The good causes funding is distributed by the Manx Lottery Trust.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mlt.org.im/|publisher=Manx Lottery Trust |title=About|website=MLT.org.im|access-date=28 February 2015}}</ref> [[Tynwald]] receives the 12p lottery duty for tickets sold in the island.\n\nTourist numbers peaked in the first half of the 20th century, prior to the boom in cheap travel to Southern Europe that also saw the decline of tourism in many similar English seaside resorts. The Isle of Man tourism board has recently invested in \"Dark Sky Discovery\" sites to diversify its tourism industry. It is expected that dark skies will generally be nominated by the public across the UK. However, the Isle of Man tourism board tasked someone from their team to nominate 27 places on the island as a civil task. This cluster of the highest quality \"Milky Way\" sites <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.darkskydiscovery.org.uk/dark-sky-discovery-sites/map.html#sites|title=Dark Sky Discovery Sites|website=Darkskydiscovery.org.uk|access-date=10 November 2017}}</ref> is now well promoted within the island. This government push has effectively given the island a headstart in the number of recognised Dark Sky sites. However, this has created a distorted view when compared to the UK where this is not promoted on a national scale. There, Dark Sky sites are expected to be nominated over time by the public across a full range of town, city and countryside locations rather than ''en masse'' by government departments.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.visitisleofman.com/placestovisit/darkskysites/darkskies.xml|title=Stargazing Sites in the Isle of Man - Isle of Man|website=Visitisleofman.com|access-date=10 November 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160911125709/http://www.visitisleofman.com/placestovisit/darkskysites/darkskies.xml|archive-date=11 September 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe Isle of Man is seen to be \"accommodating\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bitcoinregulation.world|title=Global Bitcoin Regulations|website=Bitcoinregulation.world|access-date=28 August 2018}}</ref> towards [[Bitcoin]], which is a growing technology on the island.<ref name=4coff />\n\nIn 2017 an office of [[The International Stock Exchange]] was opened to provide a boost for the island's finance industry.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.iomtoday.co.im/article.cfm?id=32400&headline=Carolyn%20Gelling%20to%20lead%20new%20stock%20exchange%20company&sectionIs=news&searchyear=2017 |title=Carolyn Gelling to lead new stock exchange company |work=IOMToday |date=9 March 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Communications ===\n{{Main|Communications on the Isle of Man}}\nThe main telephone provider on the Isle of Man is [[Manx Telecom]]. The island has two mobile operators: Manx Telecom, previously known as Manx Pronto, and [[Sure (company)|Sure]]. [[Cloud9 (service provider)|Cloud9]] operated as a third mobile operator on the island for a short time, but has since withdrawn.{{citation needed|date=November 2017}} Broadband internet services are available through four local providers: Wi-Manx, Domicilium, Manx Computer Bureau and [[Manx Telecom]]. The island does not have its own [[International Telecommunication Union|ITU]] [[list of country calling codes|country code]], but is accessed via the British country code (+44), and the island's telephone numbers are part of the [[Telephone numbers in the United Kingdom|British telephone numbering plan]], with local dialling codes 01624 for landlines and 07524, 07624 and 07924 for mobiles. Calls to the island from the UK however, are generally charged differently from those within the UK, and may or may not be included in any \"inclusive minutes\" packages.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.productsandservices.bt.com/consumer/assets/downloads/BT_PhoneTariff_Residential.pdf|title=Phone Tariff Residential|work=BT.com |publisher=[[BT Group]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://international.o2.co.uk/internationaltariffs/calling_abroad_from_uk|title=Calling abroad from the UK|work=O2.com |publisher=Telef\u00f3nica Europe}}</ref>\n\nIn 1996, the Isle of Man Government obtained permission to use the [[.im]] national [[top-level domain]] (TLD), and has ultimate responsibility for its use. The domain is managed from day to day by Domicilium, an island-based internet service provider.\n\nIn December 2007, the [[Manx Electricity Authority]] and its telecommunications subsidiary, e-llan Communications, commissioned the laying of a new fibre-optic link that connects the island to a worldwide fibre-optic network.\n\nThe Isle of Man has three radio stations: [[Manx Radio]], [[Energy FM (Isle of Man)|Energy FM]] and [[3 FM (Isle of Man)|3 FM]].\n\nThere is no insular television service, but local transmitters retransmit British mainland digital broadcasts via the free-to-air [[digital terrestrial]] service [[Freeview (UK)|Freeview]]. The Isle of Man is served by [[BBC North West]] for [[BBC One]] and [[BBC Two]] television services, and [[ITV Granada]] for [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]].\n\nMany television services are available by satellite, such as [[Sky (UK & Ireland)|Sky]], and [[Freesat]] from the group of satellites at [[Astra 28.2\u00b0E|28.2\u00b0 East]], as well as services from a range of other satellites around Europe such as the [[SES Astra|Astra]] satellites at [[Astra 19.2\u00b0E|19.2\u00b0 east]] and [[Hotbird]].\n\nThe Isle of Man has three newspapers, all weeklies, and all owned by [[Isle of Man Newspapers]], a division of the Edinburgh media company [[Johnston Press]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.johnstonpress.co.uk/jpplc/ourbusiness/publishingdivision/division.jsp | title = Our Business | publisher = Johnston Press | access-date = 12 September 2011 }}{{dead link|date=March 2020|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> The ''[[Isle of Man Courier]]'' (distribution 36,318) is free and distributed to homes on the island. The other two newspapers are ''[[Isle of Man Examiner]]'' (circulation 13,276) and the ''[[Manx Independent]]'' (circulation 12,255).<ref>\n{{cite web |title=Isle of Man Newspapers |work=IOMToday |publisher=[[Isle of Man Newspapers]] |url= http://www.iomtoday.co.im/newspaper.aspx  |access-date=4 September 2008 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20080822194758/http://www.iomtoday.co.im/newspaper.aspx |archive-date=22 August 2008 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nPostal services are the responsibility of [[Isle of Man Post]], which took over from the British [[General Post Office]] in 1973.\n\n=== Transport ===\n{{Main|Transport in the Isle of Man}}\n[[File:Douglas Sea Terminal - Isle of Man - kingsley - 20-APR-09.jpg|thumb|right|Sea Terminal front fa\u00e7ade]]\nThere is a comprehensive bus network, operated by the government-owned bus operator [[Bus Vannin]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.im/categories/travel-traffic-and-motoring/bus-and-rail/|title=Isle of Man Government - Bus and Rail|website=Gov.im|access-date=12 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Isle of Man Sea Terminal]] in Douglas has regular ferries to and from [[Heysham]] and to and from [[Liverpool]], with a more restricted timetable operating in winter. There are also limited summer-only services to and from [[Belfast]] and [[Dublin]]. The Dublin route also operates at Christmas. At the time of the [[Isle of Man TT]] a limited number of sailings operate to and from [[Larne Harbour railway station|Larne]] in [[Northern Ireland]]. All ferries are operated by the [[Isle of Man Steam Packet Company]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.steam-packet.com/?__SPCoWinID=fb3a8cbb-61ce-40aa-bf27-95e1d8d2e301|title=Steam Packet Company|website=Steam-packet.com|access-date=10 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe only commercial airport on the island is the [[Isle of Man Airport]] at [[Ronaldsway]]. There are direct scheduled and chartered flights to numerous airports in the United Kingdom and Ireland.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.im/categories/travel-traffic-and-motoring/isle-of-man-airport/|title=Isle of Man Government - Isle of Man Airport|website=Gov.im|access-date=10 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe island has a total of {{convert|688|mi}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.isleofman.com/tourism/about/|title=Isle of Man \u2013 About the Island|website=Isleofman.com|access-date=10 November 2017|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080225093426/http://www.isleofman.com/tourism/about|archive-date=25 February 2008}}</ref> of public roads, all of which are paved. There is no overriding national speed limit; only local speed limits are set, and some roads have no speed limit. Rules about reckless driving and most other driving regulations are enforced in a similar way to the UK.<ref name=\"speed01\">{{cite web |url=http://www.iomguide.com/drivingontheisleofman.php |title=Driving on the Isle of Man |access-date=8 June 2010 |publisher=Maxima Systems |work=Isle of Man Guide |date=2005}}</ref> There is a requirement for regular vehicle examinations for some vehicles (similar to the MoT test in the UK).<ref>{{cite web | title=Vehicle examination | website=Isle of Man Government | date=1988-01-01 | url=https://www.gov.im/categories/travel-traffic-and-motoring/drivers-and-vehicles/vehicle-registration-and-licensing/vehicle-examination/ | access-date=2019-08-15}}</ref>\n\nThe island used to have an extensive narrow-gauge railway system, both steam-operated and electric, but the majority of the steam railway tracks were taken out of service many years ago, and the track removed. {{as of|2019}}, there is a [[Isle Of Man Railway|steam railway]] between Douglas and Port Erin, an [[Manx Electric Railway|electric railway]] between Douglas and Ramsey and an [[Snaefell Mountain Railway|electric mountain railway]] which climbs [[Snaefell]].<ref name=\"Heritage\" />\n\nOne of the oldest operating horse tram services is located on the sea front in the capital, [[Douglas, Isle of Man|Douglas]]. It was founded in 1876.<ref name=\"Heritage\">{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.im/categories/travel-traffic-and-motoring/bus-and-rail/heritage-railways/ |title=Heritage Railways |access-date=8 November 2017 |publisher=Isle of Man Government |work=Gov.im |date=2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Space commerce ===\nThe Isle of Man has become a centre for emerging [[Private spaceflight|private space travel]] companies.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/personalfinance/offshorefinance/8644850/Lift-off-for-Isle-of-Mans-quest-to-join-space-race.html | title = Lift-off for Isle of Man's quest to join space race | work = [[The Daily Telegraph]] | date = 22 July 2011 | access-date =12 September 2011 | last = Goodman | first = Mike}}</ref> A number of the competitors in the [[Google Lunar X Prize]], a $30&nbsp;million competition for the first privately funded team to send a robot to the Moon, are based on the island. The team summit for the X Prize was held on the island in October 2010.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.googlelunarxprize.com/media-center/press-release/lunar-entrepreneurs-converge-on-isle-of-man-for-google-lunar-x-prize-summ | title = Lunar Entrepreneurs Converge on Isle of Man for Google Lunar X PRIZE Summit | date = 18 October 2010 | access-date = 12 September 2011 | work = GoogleLunarXPrize.com | url-status=dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20120402103131/http://www.googlelunarxprize.com/media-center/press-release/lunar-entrepreneurs-converge-on-isle-of-man-for-google-lunar-x-prize-summ | archivedate = 2 April 2012 | df = dmy-all }}</ref> In January 2011 two research space stations owned by [[Excalibur Almaz]] arrived on the island and were kept in an aircraft hangar at the airfield at the former [[RAF Jurby]] near [[Jurby]].<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-isle-of-man-12128590 | work = BBC News | title = Research space stations arrive on Isle of Man | date = 6 January 2011 | access-date =12 September 2011 }}</ref>\n\n=== Electricity supply ===\nThe electricity supply on the Isle of Man is run by the [[Manx Electricity Authority]]. The Isle of Man is connected to [[National Grid (Great Britain)|Great Britain's national grid]] by a 40&nbsp;[[Megawatt|MW]] [[alternating current]] link ([[Isle of Man to England Interconnector]]). There are also hydroelectric, natural gas and diesel generators. The government has also planned a 700 MW offshore wind farm, roughly half the size of [[Walney Wind Farm]].<ref name=4coff>{{cite web|url=https://www.4coffshore.com/windfarms/windfarms.aspx?windfarmid=IM01|title=Isle of Man Offshore Wind Farm|website= 4C Offshore|date=1 February 2017|accessdate=14 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Culture ==\n{{Main|Culture of the Isle of Man}}\nThe culture of the Isle of Man is often promoted as being influenced by its [[Celt]]ic and, to a lesser extent, its [[Norsemen|Norse]] origins. Proximity to the UK, popularity as a UK tourist destination in Victorian times, and immigration from Britain has meant that the cultures of Great Britain have been influential at least since [[Revestment (Isle of Man)|Revestment]]. Revival campaigns have attempted to preserve the surviving vestiges of Manx culture after a long period of [[Anglicisation]], and there has been significantly increased interest in the Manx language, history and musical tradition.\n\n=== Language ===\n{{Main|Languages of the Isle of Man}}\n[[File:Douglas Isle of Man welcome sign.jpg|thumb|right|A bilingual sign in the Isle of Man featuring [[Manx language|Manx]] and English]]\n\nThe official language of the Isle of Man is [[English language|English]]. Manx has traditionally been spoken but has been stated to be \"critically endangered\".<ref name=\"ManxUNESCO\">\n{{cite web\n |title       = UNESCO accepts Manx language is not 'extinct'\n |url         = http://www.gov.im/lib/news/cso/unescoacceptsman.xml\n |date        = 19 August 2009\n |publisher   = Isle of Man Government\n |access-date  = 20 August 2009\n |url-status     = dead\n |archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20110511200853/http://www.gov.im/lib/news/cso/unescoacceptsman.xml\n |archive-date = 11 May 2011\n |df          = dmy-all\n}}</ref> However it now has a growing number of young speakers.\n\nManx is a [[Goidelic languages|Goidelic]] Celtic language and is one of a number of [[insular Celtic languages]] spoken in the British Isles.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.swarthmore.edu/SocSci/Linguistics/2011thesis/PDFs/CarpenterBMC.pdf | title = Mind Your P's and Q's: Revisiting the Insular Celtic hypothesis through working towards an original phonetic reconstruction of Insular Celtic | date = 2011 | access-date =17 September 2011 | first = Rachel N. | last = Carpenter }}</ref> Manx has been officially recognised as a legitimate [[autochthonous language|autochthonous]] [[regional language]] under the [[European Charter for Regional or Minority Languages]], ratified by the United Kingdom on 27 March 2001 on behalf of the Isle of Man government.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.bbc.co.uk/voices/multilingual/manx.shtml | title = Manx today by Phil Kelly | first = Phil | last = Kelly | work = BBC News | access-date =17 September 2011 }}</ref>\n\nManx is closely related to [[Irish language|Irish]] and [[Scottish Gaelic]], but is orthographically [[sui generis]].\n\nOn the island, the [[Manx language|Manx]] greetings ''{{lang|gv|moghrey mie}}'' (good morning) and ''{{lang|gv|fastyr mie}}'' (good afternoon) can often be heard.<ref>{{cite book | title = An Introduction to Applied Linguistics | edition = 2nd The Manx | last = Davies | first = Alan | publisher = Edinburgh University Press | date = 2007 | isbn = 978-0-7486-3354-8 }}</ref> As in Irish and Scottish Gaelic, the concepts of \"evening\" and \"afternoon\" are referred to with one word.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.visitisleofman.com/culture/ | title = Manx Culture | access-date =17 September 2011 | work = VisitIsleOfMan.com }}</ref> Two other Manx expressions often heard are ''Gura mie eu'' (\"Thank you\"; familiar 2nd person singular form ''Gura mie ayd'') and ''{{lang|gv|traa dy liooar}}'', meaning \"time enough\", this represents a stereotypical view of the Manx attitude to life.<ref>{{cite book | page = 274 | title = The Folk-Lore of the Isle of Man | first = Moore | last = Arthur William | publisher = Forgotten Books | edition = Reprint | date = 1971 | isbn = 1-60506-183-2}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.iomtoday.co.im/news/education/moscow_manx_cheese_1_2908142?showResult=true&pollContentId=7.52601 | archive-url = https://archive.today/20120804201941/http://www.iomtoday.co.im/news/education/moscow_manx_cheese_1_2908142?showResult=true&pollContentId=7.52601 | url-status=dead | archive-date = 4 August 2012 | title = Moscow Manx cheese | work = IOMToday | date = 8 January 2011 | access-date = 17 September 2011 }}</ref>\n\nIn the 2011 Isle of Man census, approximately 1,800 residents could read, write, and speak the Manx language.<ref name=\"census-2011\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.im/media/207882/census2011reportfinalresized_1_.pdf|title=Isle of Man Census Report 2011|website=Gov.im|accessdate=19 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Symbols ===\n[[File:The Legs of Man - Isle of Man Triskelion - kingsley - 19-APR-09.jpg|right|thumb|A sculpture of the Manx [[triskelion]] in front of [[Isle of Man Airport|Ronaldsway Airport]] terminal]]\n\nFor centuries, the island's symbol has been the so-called \"three legs of Mann\" ({{lang-gv|Tree Cassyn Vannin}}), a [[triskelion]] of three legs conjoined at the thigh. The Manx triskelion, which dates back with certainty to the late 13th century, is of uncertain origin. It has been suggested that its origin lies in [[Sicily]], an island which has been associated with the triskelion since ancient times.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Archeologia del Mediterraneo: Studi in onore di Ernesto De Miro |date=2003 |publisher=L'Erma di Bretschneider |isbn=978-88-8265-134-3 |pages=735\u2013736|editor1-last=Fiorentini |editor1-first=Graziella |editor2-last=De Miro |editor2-first=Ernesto |editor3-last=Calderone |editor3-first=Anna |editor4-last=Caccamo Caltabiano |editor4-first=Maria|ref=harv}}{{inconsistent citations|date=December 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last=Wilson |first=RJA |date=2000 |title=On the Trail of the Triskeles: From the McDonald Institute to Archaic Greek Sicily |journal=[[Cambridge Archaeological Journal]] |volume=10 |issue=1 |pages=35\u201361 |doi=10.1017/S0959774300000020 }}</ref>\n\nThe symbol appears in the island's [[Flag of the Isle of Man|official flag]] and [[Coat of arms of the Isle of Man|official coat of arms]], as well as [[currency of the Isle of Man|its currency]]. The Manx triskelion may be reflected in the island's motto, {{lang-la|Quocunque jeceris stabit}}, which appears as part of the island's coat of arms. The Latin motto translates into English as \"whichever way you throw, it will stand\"<ref name=\"kinvig-9192\" /> or \"whithersoever you throw it, it will stand\".<ref name=\"govmotto\">{{cite web |url=http://www.gov.im/categories/business-and-industries/iom-key-facts-guide/island-facts/ |title=Island Facts |access-date=15 January 2016 |publisher=Public Services, Isle of Man Government |work=Gov.im |ref=harv |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304050532/https://www.gov.im/categories/business-and-industries/iom-key-facts-guide/island-facts/ |archivedate=4 March 2016}}{{inconsistent citations}}</ref> It dates to the late 17th century when it is known to have appeared on the island's coinage.<ref name=\"kinvig-9192\">{{Cite book |last=Kinvig |first=R.H. |title=The Isle of Man: A social, cultural and political history |date=1975 |publisher=Charles E. Tuttle |location=Rutland, Vermont |isbn=0-8048-1165-2 |pages=91\u201392 |ref=harv}}{{inconsistent citations}}</ref> It has also been suggested that the motto originally referred to the poor quality of coinage which was common at the time\u2014as in \"however it is tested it will pass\".<ref name=\"manxnotebook-legs\">{{cite web |url=http://www.isle-of-man.com/manxnotebook/history/legs.htm |title=The Three Legs of Man |access-date=15 September 2011 |work=Isle-of-Man.com) |ref=harv}}. This webpage cited: {{Cite journal |last=Wagner |first=A. R. |title=The Origin of the Arms of Man |date=1959\u20131960 |volume=6 |journal=Manx Museum |ref=harv}}. This webpage also cited: {{Cite journal |last=Megaw |first=B. R. S. |title=The Ship Seals of the Kings of Man |date=1959\u20131960 |volume=6 |journal=Manx Museum |ref=harv}}{{inconsistent citations|date=December 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe ragwort or ''[[cushag]]'' is the Manx national flower.<ref>[//www.gov.im/categories/business-and-industries/iom-key-facts-guide/island-facts/ Island Facts \u2013 Isle of Man Public Services]. Gov.im (12 July 1996). Retrieved on 29 July 2013.</ref>\n\n=== Religion ===\n{{See also|Diocese of Sodor and Man}}\n[[File:Peel Cathedral 01.JPG|thumb|right|upright=0.9|[[Peel Cathedral]]]]\n\nThe predominant religious tradition of the island is [[Christianity]]. Before the Protestant Reformation, the island had a long history as part of the unified [[Western Church]], and in the years following the Reformation, the religious authorities on the island, and later the population of the island, accepted the religious authority of the British monarchy and the [[Church of England]].<ref>\n{{cite web\n| last=Moore\n| first=A.\n| title=Diocesan Histories. Sodor and Mann.\n| url=http://www.isle-of-man.com/manxnotebook/fulltext/dh1893/index.htm\n}}</ref> It has also come under the influence of Irish religious tradition. The island forms a separate diocese called [[Diocese of Sodor and Man|Sodor and Man]], which in the distant past comprised the medieval kingdom of Man and the Scottish isles (\"Su\u00f0reyjar\" in Old Norse). It now consists of 16 parishes,<ref>{{cite web | last=Gumbley | first=Ken | title=Diocese of Sodor and Man | website=Welcome to Kirk Braddan | date=2012-03-01 | url=http://www.gumbley.net/diocese.htm | access-date=2019-08-15}}</ref> and since 1541<ref>Act of Parliament (1541) 33 Hen.8 c.31</ref> has formed part of the [[Province of York]].<ref>{{cite web | title=England-Sodor & Man | website=Anglican Communion | date=2012-05-28 | url=http://www.anglicancommunion.org/tour/diocese.cfm?Idind=214 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120528223800/http://www.anglicancommunion.org/tour/diocese.cfm?Idind=214 | archive-date=2012-05-28 | url-status=unfit | access-date=2019-08-15}}</ref> (These modern ecclesiastical parishes do not correspond to the island's ancient parishes mentioned in this article under \"Local Government\", but more closely reflect the current geographical distribution of population.)\n\nOther Christian churches also operate on the Isle of Man. The second largest denomination is the [[Methodist Church of Great Britain|Methodist Church]], whose Isle of Man District is close in numbers to the Anglican diocese. There are eight Catholic parish churches, included in the [[Catholic Archdiocese of Liverpool]],<ref>{{cite web | title=The Archdiocese of Liverpool  | website=Liverpool Catholic | url=http://www.liverpoolcatholic.org.uk | access-date=2019-08-15}}</ref> as well as a presence of [[Eastern Orthodox]] Christians. Additionally there are five [[Baptist]] churches, four [[Pentecostal]] churches, the [[Salvation Army]], a [[The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints in the Isle of Man|ward]] of [[The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints]], two congregations of [[Jehovah's Witnesses]], two [[United Reformed]] churches, as well as other Christian churches. There is a small [[Muslim]] community, with its own mosque in Douglas, and there is also a small [[Jewish]] community, see the [[history of the Jews in the Isle of Man]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gov.im/IsleOfMan/religion.xml|title=Religious Faiths and Organisations|date=2012-05-28|website=Isle of Man Government|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20030608055741/http://www.gov.im/IsleOfMan/religion.xml|archive-date=2003-06-08|url-status=unfit|access-date=2019-08-15}}</ref>\n\n=== Myth, legend and folklore ===\n[[File:Isle of Man Peel Castle.jpg|right|upright=1.15|thumb|[[Peel Castle]]]]\nIn Manx mythology, the island was ruled by the sea god [[Manann\u00e1n mac Lir|Manann\u00e1n]], who would draw his misty cloak around the island to protect it from invaders. One of the principal folk theories about the origin of the name ''Mann'' is that it is named after Manann\u00e1n.\n\nIn the Manx tradition of [[folklore]], there are many stories of mythical creatures and characters. These include the {{lang|gv|[[Buggane]]}}, a malevolent spirit which, according to legend, blew the roof off St Trinian's Church in a fit of rage; the {{lang|gv|[[Fenodyree]]}}; the {{lang|gv|[[Glashtyn]]}}; and the {{lang|gv|[[Moddey Dhoo]]}}, a [[black dog (ghost)|ghostly black dog]] which wandered the walls and corridors of [[Peel Castle]].\n\nThe Isle of Man is also said to be home to [[mooinjer veggey|fairies]], known locally as \"the little folk\" or \"themselves\". There is a famous [[Fairy Bridge (Isle of Man)|Fairy Bridge]], and it is said to be bad luck if one fails to wish the fairies good morning or afternoon when passing over it. It used to be a tradition to leave a coin on the bridge to ensure good luck. Other types of fairies are the {{lang|gv|Mi'raj}} and the {{lang|gv|[[Arkan Sonney]]}}.\n\nAn old Irish story tells how [[Lough Neagh]] was formed when Ireland's legendary giant [[Fionn mac Cumhaill]] (commonly anglicised to Finn McCool) ripped up a portion of the land and tossed it at a Scottish rival. He missed, and the chunk of earth landed in the [[Irish Sea]], thus creating the island.\n\nPeel Castle has been proposed as a possible location of the Arthurian [[Avalon]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.electricscotland.com/history/avalon.htm|title=Avalon's Location|website=Electricscotland.com|access-date=28 February 2015}}</ref> or as the location of the Grail Castle, site of [[Lancelot]]'s encounter with the sword bridge of King [[Maleagant]].<ref>King Arthur, Norma Lorre Goodrich, Harper and Row, 1989, p. 318</ref>\n\nOne of the most often-repeated myths is that people found guilty of witchcraft were rolled down Slieau Whallian, a hill near St John's, in a barrel. However this is a 19th-century legend which comes from a Scottish legend, which in turn comes from a German legend. It never happened. Separately, a witchcraft museum was opened at the Witches Mill, Castletown in 1951. There has never actually been a witches' coven on that site; the myth was only created with the opening of the museum.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iomtoday.co.im/news/isle-of-man-news/manx-witchcraft-and-sorcery-probed-by-academic-1-1744837|title=Manx witchcraft and sorcery probed by academic - Isle of Man Today<!-- Bot generated title -->|website=Iomtoday.co.im|access-date=10 November 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151227154121/http://www.iomtoday.co.im/news/isle-of-man-news/manx-witchcraft-and-sorcery-probed-by-academic-1-1744837|archivedate=27 December 2015}}</ref> However, there has been a strong tradition of herbalism and the use of charms to prevent and cure illness and disease in people and animals<ref>{{Cite book|chapter-url=http://www.isle-of-man.com/manxnotebook/iomnhas/lm3p303.htm|title=Yn Lioar Manninagh: The Journal of the Isle of Man Natural History and Antiquarian Society|last=Nisbet|first=Robert A|last2=Rhys|first2=John|date=1897|publisher=Brown & Sons|isbn=|volume=Vol 3|location=Douglas|pages=303\u2013314|language=English|chapter=Folk-Medicine in the Isle of Man \u2013 A. W. Moore, M. A.|oclc=1110392917}}</ref><ref>{{cite book | last=Chiverrell | first=R. | last2=Belchem | first2=J. | last3=Thomas | first3=G. | last4=Duffy | first4=S. | last5=Mytum | first5=H. | title=A New History of the Isle of Man: The modern period 1830-1999 | publisher=Liverpool University Press | series=A New History of the Isle of Man | year=2000 | isbn=978-0-85323-726-6 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yjHHVG_aiOAC&pg=PA353 | access-date=2019-08-15 | page=353}}</ref>\n\n=== Music ===\n{{main|Music of the Isle of Man}}\n\n[[File:Bee Gees Plaque - Union Mills IOM - kingsley - 21-APR-09.jpg|right|thumb|[[Bee Gees]] plaque at Maitland Terrace/Strang Road intersection in [[Union Mills]], Isle of Man]]\nThe music of the Isle of Man reflects [[Celt]]ic, Norse and other influences, including from its neighbours, [[Scotland]], Ireland, England and [[Wales]]. A wide range of music is performed on the island, such as rock, blues, jazz and pop. However, its traditional folk music has undergone a revival since the 1970s, starting with a music festival called {{lang|gv|[[Yn \u00c7hruinnaght]]}} in [[Ramsey, Isle of Man|Ramsey]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ceolas.org/Regions/Manx-article.html|title=Trad music in the Isle of Man|website=Ceolas.org|access-date=28 February 2015}}</ref> This was part of a general revival of the Manx language and culture after the death of the last native speaker of Manx in 1974.\nThe Isle of Man was mentioned in the [[The Who|Who]] song \"[[Happy Jack (song)|Happy Jack]]\" as the homeland of the song's titular character, who is always in a state of ecstasy, no matter what happens to him. The song 'The Craic was 90 in the Isle of Man' by [[Christy Moore]] describes a lively visit during the Island's tourism heyday. The Island is also the birthplace of Maurice, Robin and Barry Gibb, of the [[Bee Gees]].\n\n=== Food ===\nIn the past, the basic national dish of the island was ''spuds and herrin'', boiled potatoes and herring. This plain dish was supported by the subsistence farmers of the island, who [[Crofting|crofted]] the land and fished the sea for centuries. A more recent claim for the title of national dish could be the ubiquitous chips, cheese and gravy. This dish, which is similar to [[poutine]], is found in most of the island's fast-food outlets, and consists of thick cut [[French fried potatoes|chips]], covered in shredded Manx [[Cheddar cheese]] and topped with a thick gravy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.isleofman.com/attractions/cuisine/|title=Attractions :: isleofman.com|last=isleofman.com|website=Isleofman.com|access-date=10 November 2017}}</ref> However, as of the Isle of Man Food & Drink Festival 2018, [[Queen scallop|queenies]] have been crowned the Manx national dish.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.locate.im/articles/national-dish-of-the-isle-of-man-}}</ref>\n\nSeafood has traditionally accounted for a large proportion of the local diet. Although commercial fishing has declined in recent years, local delicacies include Manx [[kipper]]s (smoked herring) which are produced by the smokeries in Peel on the west coast of the island, albeit mainly from [[North Sea]] herring these days.<ref name=\"Assoc1971\">{{cite book|title=American Motorcyclist|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=ffYDAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA22|access-date=12 September 2011|date=November 1971|publisher=American Motorcyclist Association|page=22|issn=0277-9358}}</ref> The smokeries also produce other specialities including smoked salmon and bacon.\n\nCrab, lobster and scallops are commercially fished, and the [[queen scallop]] (''queenies'') is regarded as a particular delicacy, with a light, sweet flavour.<ref>{{cite web | title = Scallops the main ingredient of unique gathering for foodies; SUN, sea, sand and shellfish | last = Evans | first = Ann | url = http://www.thefreelibrary.com/Scallops+the+main+ingredient+of+unique+gathering+for+foodies%3B+SUN,...-a0200817093 | work = Coventry Evening Telegraph |publisher = Coventry Newspapers |via=TheFreeLibrary.com | date = 30 May 2009 | access-date =12 September 2011}}</ref> Cod, [[Common ling|ling]] and mackerel are often angled for the table, and freshwater trout and salmon can be taken from the local rivers and lakes, supported by the government fish hatchery at Cornaa on the east coast.\n\nCattle, sheep, pigs and poultry are all commercially farmed; Manx lamb from the hill farms is a popular dish. The [[Manx Loaghtan|Loaghtan]], the indigenous breed of Manx sheep, has a rich, dark meat that has found favour with chefs,<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.langleychase.co.uk/ | title = Award winning organic lamb | publisher = Langley Chase Organic Farm | last = Kallaway | first = Jane | access-date =12 September 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.gov.im/lib/docs/iomfinance/factsheets/isleofmanproduce.pdf | title = Purely Isle of Man | publisher = Isle of Man Department of Finance | access-date = 12 September 2011 | url-status=dead | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20121012054640/http://www.gov.im/lib/docs/iomfinance/factsheets/isleofmanproduce.pdf | archive-date = 12 October 2012 | df = dmy-all }}</ref> featuring in dishes on the BBC's ''[[MasterChef (UK TV series)|MasterChef]]'' series.\n\nManx cheese has also found some success, featuring smoked and herb-flavoured varieties, and is stocked by many of the UK's supermarket chains.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://isleofman.isle-news.com/archives/isle-of-man-oak-smoked-mature-cheddar-wins-bronze-medal-at-the-british-cheese-awards-2010/6768/ | title = Isle of Man Oak Smoked Mature Cheddar Wins Bronze Medal at The British Cheese Awards 2010 | work = Isle News | date = 2010 | access-date = 12 September 2011 | url-status=dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20120325175544/http://isleofman.isle-news.com/archives/isle-of-man-oak-smoked-mature-cheddar-wins-bronze-medal-at-the-british-cheese-awards-2010/6768/ | archivedate = 25 March 2012 | df = dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.iomtoday.co.im/news/isle-of-man-news/bumper_sales_for_manx_cheese_1_1750532 | archive-url = https://archive.today/20120803063502/http://www.iomtoday.co.im/news/isle-of-man-news/bumper_sales_for_manx_cheese_1_1750532 | url-status=dead | archive-date = 3 August 2012 | title = Bumper Sales for Manx Cheese | date = 15 October 2003 | access-date = 12 September 2011 | work=IOMToday}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.isleofman.com/News/article.aspx?article=5017 | title = Success at World Cheese Awards | access-date =12 September 2011 | date = 22 March 2007 | work = IsleOfMan.com}}</ref> Manx cheese took bronze medals in the 2005 British Cheese Awards, and sold 578 tonnes over the year. Manx cheddar has been exported to Canada where it is available in some supermarkets.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.provigo.ca/en_CA/products/productlisting/pc-black-label-isle-of-man-extra-old-cheddar-cheese-aged-14-mont0.html | title = PC Black Label English Isle of Man Extra Old Cheddar Cheese | work = Provigo | access-date = 17 November 2016 | url-status=dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20161118035745/http://www.provigo.ca/en_CA/products/productlisting/pc-black-label-isle-of-man-extra-old-cheddar-cheese-aged-14-mont0.html | archivedate = 18 November 2016 | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nBeer is brewed on a commercial scale by [[Okells|Okells Brewery]], which was established in 1850 and is the island's largest brewer; and also by [[Bushy's Brewery]] and the Hooded Ram Brewery. The Isle of Man's Pure Beer Act of 1874, which resembles the [[Germany|German]] ''[[Reinheitsgebot]]'', is still in effect: under this Act, brewers may only use water, malt, sugar and hops in their brews.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.gov.im/lib/docs/iomfinance/factsheets/isleofmanproduce.pdf | title = Purely Isle of Man | work=Gov.im | publisher = Isle of Man Government | access-date = 10 June 2015 | url-status=dead | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20130430164916/http://www.gov.im/lib/docs/iomfinance/factsheets/isleofmanproduce.pdf | archive-date = 30 April 2013 | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n=== Sport ===\n{{Main|Sport in the Isle of Man}}\nThe Isle of Man is represented as a nation in the [[Commonwealth Games]] and the [[Island Games]] and hosted the IV [[Commonwealth Youth Games]] in 2011. Manx athletes have won [[Isle of Man at the Commonwealth Games|three gold medals]] at the Commonwealth Games, including the one by cyclist [[Mark Cavendish]] in 2006 in the [[Scratch race]]. The [[International Island Games Association|Island Games]] were first held on the island in [[1985 Island Games|1985]], and again in [[2001 Island Games|2001]].\n\nIsle of Man teams and individuals participate in many sports both on and off the island including [[rugby union]], [[association football|football]], [[gymnastics]], [[field hockey]], [[netball]], [[taekwondo]], [[bowling]], obstacle course racing and [[cricket]]. It being an island, many types of watersports are also popular with residents.\n\n==== Motorcycle racing ====\n{{details|Isle of Man TT}}\nThe main international event associated with the island is the [[Isle of Man TT|Isle of Man Tourist Trophy]] race, colloquially known as \"The TT\",<ref>Wright, David. 100 Years of the Isle of Man TT: A Century of Motorcycle Racing. The Crowood Press, 2007</ref> which began in [[1907 Isle of Man TT|1907]]. It takes place in late May and early June. The TT is now an international [[road racing]] event for motorcycles, which used to be part of the World Championship, and is long considered to be one of the \"greatest motorcycle sporting events of the world\".<ref>Disko, Sasha. The Image of the \"Tourist Trophy\" and British Motorcycling in the Weimar Republic. International Journal of Motorcycle Studies, Nov 2007</ref> Taking place over a two-week period, it has become a festival for motorcycling culture, makes a huge contribution to the island's economy and has become part of Manx identity.<ref>Vaukins, Simon. The Isle of Man TT Races: Politics, Economics and National Identity. International Journal of Motorcycle Studies, Nov 2007</ref> For many, the Isle carries the title \"road racing capital of the world\".<ref>Faragher, Martin. \"Cultural History: Motor-Cycle Road Racing.\" A New History of the Isle of Man Volume V: The Modern Period 1830\u20131999. Ed. John Belchem. Liverpool: Liverpool University Press, 2000</ref>\n\nThe [[Manx Grand Prix]] is a separate motorcycle event for amateurs and private entrants that uses the same {{convert|60.70|km|mi|abbr=on}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.manxgrandprix.org/Competitors/MGP%20regulations%2009.pdf|title=2009 Manx Grand Prix Supplementary Regulations|page=4|date=2009|website=manxgrandprix.org|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120310131221/http://www.manxgrandprix.org/Competitors/MGP%20regulations%2009.pdf|archive-date=2012-03-10|url-status=dead|access-date=2019-08-15}}</ref> [[Snaefell Mountain Course]] in late August and early September.\n\n==== Cammag ====\n{{Main|Cammag}}\nPrior to the introduction of football in the 19th century, [[Cammag]] was the island's traditional sport.<ref>{{cite web\n|url=http://www.celticlife.ca/index.php/Sports/the-game-of-cammag.html\n|title=The Game of Cammag|website=Celticlife.ca\n| access-date=12 September 2011\n}}</ref> It is similar to the Irish [[hurling]] and the Scottish game of [[shinty]]. Nowadays there is an annual match at [[St John's, Isle of Man|St John's]].\n\n=== Cinema ===\n<!-- Sub-section title is a redirect target -->\nThe Isle of Man has two cinemas, both in Douglas. The Broadway Cinema is located in the government-owned and -run Villa Marina and [[Gaiety Theatre, Isle of Man|Gaiety Theatre]] complex. It has a capacity of 154 and also doubles as a conference venue.<ref>{{cite web|title=Broadway Cinema|url=http://www.gov.im/villagaiety/broadway.xml/|website=Gov.im|access-date=6 March 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130306124729/http://www.gov.im/villagaiety/broadway.xml|archivedate=6 March 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe Palace Cinema is located next to the derelict [[Castle Mona]] hotel and is operated by the Sefton Group. It has two screens: Screen One holds 293 customers, while Screen Two is smaller with a capacity of just 95. It was extensively refurbished in August 2011.<ref>{{cite web|title=Cinemas Refurbishment|url=http://www.iomtoday.co.im/lifestyle/manx-entertainment-news/palace-cinema-reopens-1-3782747/|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130412224857/http://www.iomtoday.co.im/lifestyle/manx-entertainment-news/palace-cinema-reopens-1-3782747/|url-status=dead|archive-date=12 April 2013|website=Iomtoday.co.im|access-date=6 March 2013}}</ref>\n\n=== Fauna ===\n{{Main|Manx cat|Manx Loaghtan|Biota of the Isle of Man|Extinct animals from the Isle of Man}}\n[[File:Black Manx cat.JPG|Black Manx cat|thumb|left]]\nTwo domestic animals are specifically connected to the Isle of Man, though they are also found elsewhere.\n\nThe [[Manx cat]] is a breed of cat noted for its genetic mutation that causes it to have a shortened tail. The length of this tail can range from a few inches, known as a \"stumpy\", to being completely nonexistent, or \"rumpy\". Manx cats display a range of colours and usually have somewhat longer hind legs compared to most cats. The cats have been used as a symbol of the Isle of Man on coins and stamps and at one time the Manx government operated a breeding centre to ensure the continuation of the breed.<ref>{{cite book|last= Commings|first= Karen|date= 1999|title= Manx Cats: Everything about Purchase, Care, Nutrition, Grooming, and Behavior|url= https://archive.org/details/manxcats00kare/page/7|location= |publisher= Barron's Educational|pages= [https://archive.org/details/manxcats00kare/page/7 7\u201310]|isbn= 978-0764107535|url-access= registration}}</ref>\n[[File:Manx loaghtan.jpg|thumb|right|[[Manx Loaghtan]] sheep are bred on the island for their meat.]]\nThe [[Manx Loaghtan]] sheep is a breed native to the island. It has dark brown wool and four, or sometimes six, horns. The meat is considered to be a delicacy.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/local/isleofman/hi/people_and_places/nature/newsid_8333000/8333801.stm|title=Farming the Manx Loaghtan sheep|last=|first=|date=2009-11-16|work=BBC News|access-date=2019-08-15|language=en-GB}}</ref> There are several flocks on the island and others have been started in England and [[Jersey]].\n\nA more recent arrival on the island is the [[red-necked wallaby]], which is now established on the island following an escape from the Wildlife Park.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2016/aug/14/wallabies-isle-of-man-wild-australia|title=Wallabies flourishing in the wild on Isle of Man|date=14 August 2016|access-date=10 November 2017|work=The Guardian}}</ref> The local police report an increasing number of wallaby-related calls.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2018/09/07/calls-wallaby-warning-signs-implemented-isle-man-tackle-growing/|title=Calls for wallaby warning signs to be implemented on the Isle of Man to tackle growing numbers|last=Marshall|first=Francesca|date=2018-09-07|work=The Telegraph|access-date=2019-08-15|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref>\n\nThere are also many feral goats in [[Garff]], a matter which was raised in Tynwald Court in January 2018.<ref>Tynwald Hansard 16 January 2018, Question 9</ref>\n\nIn March 2016, the Isle of Man became the first entire territory to be adopted into UNESCO's Network of [[Man and the Biosphere Programme#Biosphere reserves|Biosphere Reserves]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/travel/destinations/europe/united-kingdom/england/isle-of-man/articles/isle-of-man-added-to-unesco-biosphere-reserve-list/|title=Isle of Man awarded UNESCO status|first=Hugh |last=Morris|work=The Daily Telegraph|access-date=28 June 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Demographics ==\n{{Main|Demographics of the Isle of Man}}\n\n===Age structure===\n:0\u201314 years: 16.27% (male 7,587 /female 6,960)\n:15\u201324 years: 11.3% (male 5,354 /female 4,750)\n:25\u201354 years: 38.48% (male 17,191 /female 17,217)\n:55\u201364 years: 13.34% (male 6,012 /female 5,919)\n:65 years and over: 20.6% (male 8,661 /female 9,756) (2018 est.)<ref name=\"CIA\">{{cite web |title=Europe :: Isle of Man |url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/geos/im.html |website=[[The World Factbook]] |publisher=[[Central Intelligence Agency]] |accessdate=12 September 2019}} {{PD-notice}}</ref>\n\n=== Population density ===\n\n:131 people/km<sup>2</sup> (339 people/sq&nbsp;mi) (2005 est.)\n\n===Sex ratio===\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Sex ratios<br>(males per female)\n|-\n!Age range!!Ratio\n|- \n|At birth||1.08\n|-\n|0-14||1.09\n|- \n|15-24||1.13\n|- \n|25-54||1.00\n|-\n|55\u201364 years||1.02\n|-\n|65+||0.89\n|- \n|Total<br>population||1 (2018 est.)<ref name=\"CIA\"/>\n|}\n\n===Infant mortality rate===\n:Total: 4 deaths/1,000 live births \n:Male: 4 deaths/1,000 live births \n:Female: 4 deaths/1,000 live births (2018 est.)\n:Country comparison to the world: 191<ref name=\"CIA\"/>\n\n===Life expectancy at birth===\n:total population: 81.4 years \n:male: 79.6 years \n:female: 83.3 years (2018 est.)\n:country comparison to the world: 29\n: ''Total [[fertility rate]]'': 1.92 children born/woman (2018 est.)<ref name=\"CIA\"/>\n\n===Nationality===\n: ''noun:'' Manxman (men), Manxwoman (women)\n: ''adjective:'' Manx\n\n===National origin groups===\n: [[Manx people|Manx]] ([[Norsemen|Norse]]-[[Celt]]ic descent) \u2013 15% \n: [[British people|British]] - 60% (50% English, 5% Scottish, 5% Welsh) \n: [[Irish people|Irish]] \u2013 10% \n: [[South African people|South African]] \u2013 7%\n: [[Australians|Australian]] \u2013 5% \n: [[Americans|American]] \u2013 3%\n\n== Climate ==\nThe Isle of Man has a [[temperate]] [[oceanic climate]] ([[K\u00f6ppen climate classification|K\u00f6ppen]] ''Cfb''). Average rainfall is higher than averaged over the territory of the British Isles, because the Isle of Man is far enough from Ireland for the prevailing south-westerly winds to accumulate moisture. Average rainfall is highest at [[Snaefell]], where it is around {{convert|1900|mm}} a year. At lower levels it can be around {{convert|800|mm}} a year. The highest recorded temperature was {{convert|28.9|C|F}} at [[Ronaldsway]] on 12 July 1983.\n\nOn 10 May 2019 Chief Minister Howard Quayle stated that the [[Isle of Man Government]] recognises that a [[state of emergency]] exists due to the threat of anthropogenic [[climate change]].<ref>{{cite web | title=This is a climate change emergency | website=In the Manx Independent this week | date=2019-05-10 | url=http://www.iomtoday.co.im/article.cfm?id=48378&headline=This%20is%20a%20climate%20change%20emergency\u00a7ionIs=NEWS&searchyear=2019 | access-date=2019-08-15}}\n</ref>\n\n{{Weather box\n|location = Isle of Man (Ronaldsway)\n|metric first = yes\n|single line = yes\n|Jan record high C = 13.3\n|Feb record high C = 13.2\n|Mar record high C = 17.1\n|Apr record high C = 20.0\n|May record high C = 24.0\n|Jun record high C = 27.5\n|Jul record high C = 28.9\n|Aug record high C = 27.8\n|Sep record high C = 26.5\n|Oct record high C = 22.7\n|Nov record high C = 16.3\n|Dec record high C = 15.0\n|year record high C = 29.0\n|Jan high C = 8.2\n|Feb high C = 7.9\n|Mar high C = 9.2\n|Apr high C = 11.1\n|May high C = 14.1\n|Jun high C = 16.3\n|Jul high C = 18.1\n|Aug high C = 18.1\n|Sep high C = 16.3\n|Oct high C = 13.6\n|Nov high C = 10.9\n|Dec high C = 8.9\n|year high C = 12.8\n|Jan low C = 3.9\n|Feb low C = 3.4\n|Mar low C = 4.4\n|Apr low C = 5.4\n|May low C = 7.7\n|Jun low C = 10.2\n|Jul low C = 12.2\n|Aug low C = 12.4\n|Sep low C = 11.1\n|Oct low C = 8.9\n|Nov low C = 6.3\n|Dec low C = 4.5\n|year low C = 7.6\n|Jan record low C = -7.8\n|Feb record low C = -5.8\n|Mar record low C = -6.0\n|Apr record low C = -3.4\n|May record low C = -0.8\n|Jun record low C = 1.4\n|Jul record low C = 5.3\n|Aug record low C = 4.9\n|Sep record low C = 1.0\n|Oct record low C = -1.5\n|Nov record low C = -4.0\n|Dec record low C = -7.0\n|year record low C = -7.8\n|precipitation colour = green\n|Jan precipitation mm = 82.6\n|Feb precipitation mm = 57.5\n|Mar precipitation mm = 65.5\n|Apr precipitation mm = 55.7\n|May precipitation mm = 